result.reviews.text: Got the turkey, avocado, & swiss sandwich with soft bread. SO GOOD. the turkey was awesome (and the sandwich as a whole was even better i think). also the staff was really friendly, and prices aren't bad!
Hole in the wall deli that serves delicious lunches with frequently rotating specials. They've been here forever and I've been going for almost 15 years. Still delicious.

Horrible, at least for breakfast. Eggs came 'over done' instead of 'over easy'. Potatoes were bland. Steak was gross (it fell apart like it might have been bad!). Toast was cheap (Wonder Bread?). They swapped some super thin and overly crispy bacon for my bad steak but all and all a terrible experience. And I had to pay an extra $3 at the ATM to get cash for this place! The service wasn't rude but the guy is obviously too cool to be friendly I any way. Anyway, maybe sandwiches are better here but their breakfast made Denny's look like a 5 Star restaurant.
great for a quick deli sandwich

One experience here:
a $7 or cheaper burger that is tasty and fresh is a thing to cherish in any city.

Fresh-tasting bread was key here. Most burgers are ruined by horrible buns with a poor crumb and stale texture.

The patty complemented the bread's quality. Though the fries were crispy and inoffensive, their mealy innards were probably frozen.

All in all, an honestly quaint, affordable, and yummy little deli.

+1 on service as well.

result.adr_address: 1655 Divisadero St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.formatted_address: 1655 Divisadero St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.name: My Father's Kitchen

result.reviews.text: My wife and I had an hour to burn between our hospital visit and saw My Father's Kitchen directly across the street. Vietnamese is something we both like and regularly eat. Unfortunately, it doesn't seem like this place is ran by those with a Viet background. The food tasted...off. I ordered the spring rolls which came with a peanut dipping sauce. It was extremely sweet and lacked any real peanut flavor. My wife ordered the pho and was disappointed in the quality of the broth. We won't be going back.

I eat here as often as I can. The #10 (chicken satay) is delicious. Also, the spring rolls, papaya salad, and chicken soup are delicious. There's a #11, which is pork meatballs and pork with rice, which is also really good. This place is fast. The food is always fresh and delicious. And it's very reasonably priced--you can get a very hearty meal for well under $10. The peanut sauce that comes with the spring rolls is SO GOOD, it's almost like dessert. Can't recommend this place enough.
Mediocre pho. Not very authentic. I had to ask for hoisin sauce. Great atmosphere.

With the abundance of Vietnamese restaurants in the neighborhood, My Father's Kitchen almost has a monopoly on pho and rice dishes. They specialize on chosen, quality food - a glance at the menu won't overwhelm you as it does at other places. 

Starters, pho, rice and vermicelli noodles. As other reviewers pointed out, this is Northern Vietnamese pho, focusing on the basics: no sprouts or basil, but fresh meat, a tasty broth, and thick noodles. My favorite here is the BEEF PHO ($9) - can't go wrong with that.

Prices - it's not the Tenderloin or Sunset... expect to pay $9 for a pho and $11/12 for noodles dishes. Well worth it though as the restaurant is clean, presentation nice, and service friendly.

Noteworthy: The coffee selection includes Blue Bottle drip, nice addition to the Vietnamese coffee.
If you are in the area its worth a taste! Fresh, seasoned well with just enough spice ... satay sauce yummy over the chicken and rice!

result.formatted_address: 1862 Divisadero St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA

result.reviews.text: Great atmosphere. Stopped in while in vacation. I owned pizza shops so love a good pie...this is one. Great pepperoni.
I don't get this place..  It's basically a run of the mill pizza by the slice but they have silencing and pretend to try to be a restaurant.   I found it all confusing.
Price is right, great service friendly atmosphere.

The design is very unique, also the customer service is exceptional I really feel like I got a warm welcome.
It's very important to me the flavors and the taste and I love the crust on the pizza slices I tasted it  keep the good work.
Great pizza by the slice, try the Norty with bacon asparagus and potatoes.

result.adr_address: 1635 Divisadero St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.formatted_address: 1635 Divisadero St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.name: Cool Cravings

result.reviews.text:
Big enough menu, super friendly staff and has a juice & smoothie station. It's feel very open and spacious. 

The food is good !

Great place for breakfast, lunch or a snack!  always very friendly staff and good and fresh ingredients, cooked on site everyday. You can have a wonderful latte, with good, tasty coffee, for $3.50, which is refreshing, giving the prices in SF.

After placing my order, I was able to chat with the owner briefly who told me that he bought this space which used to be a deli. Let me say that I'm glad he did! Although finding parking may be difficult, this cafe is worth checking out.

TL;DR version:

1. HUGE selection of food - try the chicken curry bowl
2. They have a juice bar in here - try the Complete Workout
3. 5-star atmosphere / food / customer service
4. I'm coming back again

ATMOSPHERE:
I love how this cafe was pretty spacious and could accommodate approximately over 30 people. When you enter the cafe, you're met with the counter to place your order. If you look to your far right, you could see that they also have a juice bar here - how unique is that?!

FOOD:
One thing that stood out to me was the wide variety of choices Cool Cravings had! It took me a while to figure out what I wanted and asked the owner what he suggested. What's cool that he told me was that his 80-year-old father cooks the specials and that the chicken curry rice bowl was fantastic. I was eventually sold on that.

I ordered the chicken curry rice bowl while my boyfriend ordered the chicken place with rice and salad. We found a table to sit and in probably 5 minutes, the owner placed our food in front of us. From the very first bite to the last, I couldn't believe how I haven't been to this cafe yet. I feel like if I ate this every day, the law of diminishing effect would be broken because I would not get tired of this! The chicken was cooked properly and wasn't too overcooked. The potatoes were tasty and soft - just right.

We also got some juice. It's like Jamba Juice in a cafe but better! I ordered the Complete Workout, which was comprised of strawberry, banana, mango, and pineapple. The Complete Workout was literally all my favorite fruit blended into one. There's a slight sour-y tang in the aftertaste.

CUSTOMER SERVICE:
As soon as I entered the restaurant, the employee behind the counter acknowledged and greeted me with a friendly smile. I observed around the cafe and the people that worked here seemed to be super friendly. I appreciated how I was able to get to know the owner and chat a little bit, especially about the history of the cafe. One thing that I witnessed that was kind was when there was this female patron that was about to pack up, one of the employees asked if she wanted a bag before she even had to go up to the counter and ask! Staff here is on point.

I wouldn't say this place is fine-dining, but it's affordable luxury because they have 5-star food with a 5-star staff. And c'mon, where else would you find a gem like this in San Francisco?!

I highly suggest coming here and bringing your friends. I'm super excited to come back again and try the rest of their selections!

Super friendly staff. Great tasty sandwiches, made to order.  Lots of choices.  Everything is always fresh.  You'll enjoy the juice bar.  They really work hard at ensuring you are satisfied and making suggestions with your orders if you are indecisive like myself.   Fast service.
The food was great. The chicken was juicy and melted in your mouth. A great gluten-free option. Not 5 stars because I think the rice was a day old, but the flavor of everything was great.

result.adr_address: 2232 Bush St, San Francisco, CA 94115-3122, USA
result.formatted_address: 2232 Bush St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.name: OTD

result.reviews.text: Delicious, upmarket Vietnamese fare - both the fresh and fried spring rolls as appetizers are great! Easier to get into than Slanted Door as well.

The milk tea actually was better than I expected it to be. The tea flavor is there initially, but it's not full bodied enough to carry a satisfying finish. It's also a bit too floral for me and could use some more earthy and malty notes. I have to say that it's really not bad though. Just having a semblance of tea flavor already puts it miles ahead of other highly rated establishments like Tea Way, T-Pumps, and Boba Guys. 

What really hurt OTD was its food. I had the pork and shrimp wonton noodle soup, and everything was pretty bland. The broth, noodles, and wontons all didn't have any real discernible flavors. I might be a little biased since I've never been a huge fan of Charles Phan, but I really feel that it needed to have a lot more flavor for the price that it commands.

Bit swanky / pricey for me.... Nice though. Went for a friend's going away to the Ukraine and she has a great time with about 10 of us. Parking was easier than I expected.... Maybe I just got lucky.
  :-)
Always interesting things on the menu, order everything family style. Must have: short ribs, fried chicken and sticky rice.
LOVED everything about this place, the ambience, the service, and the fabulous food. Will be back!!!

result.adr_address: 1901 Divisadero St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.formatted_address: 1901 Divisadero St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.name: My Ivy

result.reviews.text: Pretty good food, if they deliver what you order. If they don't, though, don't expect them to fix it.
Okay Thai choice in the neighborhood. Their Tom Kha is good, with little hints of spiciness. I also liked the Pad Thai.

Yea for good Thai delivery in SF! I used to be addicted to the massaman curry and red curry with pumpkin or duck. Still enjoy them, but they seem to have lost the oomph they once had. But the stir-fried dishes have greatly improved. The garlic pork last time was truly impressive. Love the tom ka (and I'm PICKY about my tom ka) and seafood soups. Great appetizers: crispy curry chicken flour cups, angel wings, mee krab. Skip the satay; it's meh. You'll find better elsewhere.

I'm a Seattle Thai enthusiast, which makes finding Thai elsewhere difficult. Didn't try this place for years because of the awful name, but am glad a native pointed me in its direction.

Despite the fact that this place almost always seems empty, the food is actually quite good.  I am a fan of the pad thai with chicken, the lettuce wraps and the spring rolls.  The soups are also very good.  Service is decent and food generally comes out pretty quick.  To-go orders sometimes seem to take longer than they should.  Prices are very reasonable and overall one of my favorite places for Thai food in the city.
i llike thier pad thai!!! so great and i like the chicken satay too!

result.adr_address: 1761 Fillmore St, San Francisco, CA 94115-3129, USA
result.formatted_address: 1761 Fillmore St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.name: Pride of the Mediterranean

result.reviews.text:
Great choice of hookas and other regional food and drinks. A bit pricey for the offered goods.
Great owner. Very talkative in a good way.

Came here last night for 3 of my friends birthdays! We were in a large group and still the service was great! The prices are very reasonable and the food was awesome! Babs Diaphanous  was amazing and also my main meal of chicken Schweitzer no complaints. I tried also the Falstaff and hummus and well winners. Def would come back.

Food was bland. Service was slow. When asked about garlic sauce owner? stated they don't change their menu. Whatever that means. Owner also over charged us because he couldn't calculate our split bill.

I've read some bad reviews of this place but I disagree. You just have to go in expecting a certain thing. It felt very similar to places I've been in Turkey and other countries. So if you're looking for authentic... this place feels like the real deal in that the food is good but not great, they have decent drinks, a hookah porch, lots of decorations and chill atmosphere. It's not one of those places claiming authentic food but then has a super chic or Americanized experience.

We come to the place for a workday afternoon tea and Hookah! The place is empty!! No one else but us! We sit in the more comfortable corner, the guy forces us to move to a smaller table because we are a party of two!!!! Not-so- Awesome customer service!!!!

result.adr_address: 1911 Fillmore St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.formatted_address: 1911 Fillmore St, San Francisco, CA 94115, USA
result.name: SPQR

result.reviews.text: Did the pasta tasting menu and the wine pairing on a rainy Thursday evening... AMAZING!  I'll happily skip the pasta course for the rest of the year!  After savoring 5 courses of pasta preparations where each was unique, complex, and bursting with flavor.  You know where those dollars are going with each mouthful... bring your wallet: $$$$  Space is small and a bit stuffy, if you sit at a 2-top you will be inches away from the table next to you.
Delicious pastas and the cozy-yet-upscale atmosphere is great, but taking off a star as it's a little pricey for what it is.

Tajarin and truffles... The pasta was delicate and delicious. My friend buckwheat fusilli, also so tender and tasty. The main course was Wagyu beef with fregola and arugula. The flavors of the pasta paired really nicely with the steak. Our waitress was really well versed in their wines and helped us pair the performing wine with our meal. Service was warm, friendly and gracious.

“Meat and Potatoes” Couple Meet Culinary Excellence

In celebration of our birthdays this year, we traveled to Northern California for a week’s vacation.  Our last night was spent in San Francisco, and we asked a local friend in the culinary sciences to recommend a restaurant for a “kick ass” dinner to close out our vacation.  When he recommended SPQR, we were skeptical – we are basic “meat and potatoes” folk, and the menu looked a bit “wild”, plus one of us has gluten sensitivities; but, we decided to go for it, and to be open to new tastes.

We cannot sufficiently describe how magical the evening was.  SPQR is a lovely little restaurant sandwiched in a long block of various businesses.  The atmosphere is warm and inviting, with no excess “fru-fru”.  We were assured a table with our reservation, but opted to sit at the chef’s bar and have a front seat view to the artistry and skill at play in the creation of the various dishes.  We were in awe as we watched the care and precision used to cut and prepare the ingredients, the swirl of activity as dishes were created and cooked, and the critical eye used in the final presentation and inspection of the meals before being approved for delivery to a diner.  Chef Matthew was brilliant as he moved from place to place, preparing the dishes personally with the well-orchestrated and clearly well-rehearsed assistance of his staff.  Chef frequently dipped clean tasting spoons in his creations and thoughtfully sampled items to ensure a high quality experience for his guests.

We ditched concerns about our waistlines for the evening and went all-out.  We are completely unfamiliar with Italian wines, so our waiter assisted us in selecting lovely red and white wines aligned with our tastes.  We started with appetizers:  broccoli, hen of the wood mushrooms, smoked gouda, bread pudding and acorn prosciutto on a broccoli pesto bed; and an incredible sunchoke soup with truffle crema that is out of this world.  For entrees we had buckwheat fusilli with pork, and almond crusted sturgeon and sturgeon sausage (prepared gluten free and flavor full).  Both were a delight in each and every bite.  For dessert we had caramel budino with toasted meringue, and a delightful citrus granita shaved ice preparation for a gluten free option.  We finished off with a rich cup of espresso and a rapturous glass of Isole E Olena Chianti/Trebbiano (another on-the-spot recommendation by our waiter).

All the food was amazing, and comprised what we agree is the best meal we’ve ever had.  The wine was perfectly matched to our tastes and our meals.  Chef Matthew was amazing in his grace and mastery of his kitchen and staff.  The wait staff was excellent:  attentive without hovering and anticipating our every need and desire   The restaurant was comfortable and inviting, with enough activity to be interesting and enough quiet for intimate conversation.  We cannot image a dining experience superior to this one.  SPQR is a not-to-be-missed treat.

This place has a michelin star so the food should be great, well at least that’s what I expected. To be honest, it was even better than I hoped for. What a great resto! We sat at the chef's counter and could see five people work magic in a tiny kitchen. We had soup and pasta with all sorts of rare ingredients, and our dessert was a work of art. Great location too.

result.reviews.text: Pizza is fast and delicious. It's locally owned and the owners go out of their way to deliver great service. It is a comfortable atmosphere, nice ambiance and convenient location. I'll definitely be back

I had the meat ball sandwich. It's how I determine if the food in a place is going to be good. If they can't do a meatball sandwich right the rest of the food won't be very good. It was very good. I could taste the savory meatballs through the simmered and slightly tart sauce. The cheese was melted but not napalm hot. I talked to Amy for a couple hours on a slow night. Hadn't seen her in over 25 years and that was 2,000 miles away from the Eagle Pizzeria.
The food was great, the conversation was great and the service was excellent. And I still have pizza to look forward to!

My extended family comes to this reasonably-priced, neighborhood family-style restaurant for birthdays, in particular my uncle who loves pizza and is wheelchair-bound. Eagle Pizzeria has my family sit against the wall on the right with all the photos and mementos. It's easy to roll my uncle in and out and can easily sit 16 of us comfortably at one long table. 

We are big eaters. We usually start with double orders of the antipasto salad, garlic bread and for some in my family bowls of minestrone, spaghetti and meatballs to share, and 4 - 5 larges or extra-larges (Eagle Special, Amy "E," Meat Lovers, Hawaiian and the Margherita), with pitchers of root beer. 

Eagle's pizza is on the thick crust side with more of a tomato base sauce and not heavy cheese, Toppings are plentiful, but not overly generous. The pizzas are not heavy pies or will reach your table super burning hot. We eat gluten, so have not tried their gluten-free crust. No one is hungry after we eat and usually there is a few slices left for those who want the leftovers.

Service is efficient, but you do have to wait for the pizza. I think the wait is longer for us because of the quantity we order, the size of our party and if the place gets busy with after baseball/kid sport parties. We also start around 5:30 pm to 6 pm on Sunday nights so it's usually less crowded. Parking is also easier too without paying the meter.

Eagle does allow us to bring our own birthday cake and does not add an additional cake cutting fee per person to our final bill. They are also generous by letting us stay and linger to talk after dessert. We usually stay between 2 - 3 hrs for dinner.

result.formatted_address: 1935 Taraval St, San Francisco, CA 94116, USA
result.name: Dumpling Kitchen

result.reviews.text:
Note: Street parking. We were lucky and found a parking spot nearby in the local neighborhood.

PROs:
  * The food is pretty good. We got dumplings, green onion pancake, and vegetarian noodles. The green onion pancake was a bit different than what I've had as a kid; it's fluffier and made with the same dough (or similar) as the dumplings. 
  * Service is prompt. After sitting down and ordering, the food came out pretty quickly. The waiters were vigilant with refilling the teapot.
  * The price is fair for the amount and given the location. 

CONs:
  * The restaurant is small, so there's almost always a wait.
I liked the regular pork XLB over the other. They could use a bit more juice inside, but great overall. 20 minute wait for party of 2 on a Friday night.

This was a favorite lunch and dinner stop for dumplings and pot stickers on Taraval. Take the L  if you don't feel like walking. It's located close to Pacific and beach access. Simple decor. I didn't try other dishes on the menu. It was fun to watch the dumplings  being made in local shop windows during my morning run in the Taraval area.

We had a pretty large group here last night for a couple of friends' birthdays. For the value, Dumpling Kitchen was pretty good. It's no Michelin star restaurant but a satisfying combination of price, portion, and flavor.

XLB - The skins were way better than I expected at this price point. Their texture was smooth with the right amount of firm chewiness. Just from looking at them, the fine folds at the top was a good sign that the skins would be thin and delicate. They also didn't break open when picked up with chopstick. Not much to complain about there. The stuffing was not the best but still decent for a low end restaurant. The texture of the pork was on the grittier side, and I thought it could've had more ginger and green onions mixed in for more brightness. The broth was similar to the pork stuffing in that it could be brighter and bolder, but it still had good body and was seasoned with enough salt . The broth was also on the fattier side, which doesn't bother me, but I know some people out there prefer cleaner XLB broths. 

Braised Pork Belly with Pickled Vegetables - You can tell this restaurant probably isn't run by Shanghainese people because of kitchen staff yelling at each other in Cantonese, and this is reflected in some of the menu items. This braised pork belly dish is a traditional Hakka classic from southern China, far from Shanghai. Dumpling Kitchen's rendition is actually pretty good. The pork belly was tender, and the sauce was a good balance of sweetness and pickled earthiness. My favorite place to order this is at Hakka Restaurant in the Outer Richmond. If I had to compare the two, Hakka's sauce is thicker and richer with a more complex spice mixture. There's a slight orange peel flavor in Hakka's that separates it from the rest. Despite not being as good as Hakka's, I would have no qualms with getting the pork belly here. 

Green Onion Pancakes - Not really my cup of tea. They have the lighter and fluffier version of green onion pancakes, and I didn't think it had much green onion flavor. It kinda just tasted doughy. The crispy and layered green onion pancakes are way better.

Vegetarian Potstickers - There was a vegetarian in our group so we had an order of vegetarian potstickers. I was kinda surprised because they turned out to be pretty tasty. I probably liked them more than the pork and chive dumplings. There's a good amount of shiitake mushrooms to give it a lot of umami and earthy flavors. They also put in dried tofu (doufu gon), and it's firmer texture and five spice flavor paired well with the other ingredients in the stuffing.

Noodles with Black Bean Sauce - Not good. Sauce was not very savory and didn't taste black bean-y. Noodles were mushy and gross. Skip this.

Egg Puffs (Sah Yong) - Freshly fried and really delicious. They were light, airy, and full of eggy goodness. If I had to complain about something, it's that instead of surrounding the donuts in sugar, it's just poured all on top of the donuts. I just rolled the donut around to get the sugar everywhere.

result.reviews.text: Good fried chicken and spicy beef soup.

Every table in this place has a plate of their Korean Fried Chicken. I’ve come here a number of times and each time I don’t plan on ordering the fried chicken, yet I still order one anyway.  This is a very popular local Korean restaurant and for good reason.  Most of their dishes are fairly priced and tasty.  They usually offer a few pieces of mackerel that’s on the house as part of their banchan side dishes. Be warned though this place is relatively small and the wait could get crazy, try to catch it really early or really late.

We ate the bulgogi and a big Korean pancake, and tofu soup on the house.  All three were good and generous; the two of us tall men couldn't quite finish it all.

The service was pretty quick (on a Monday evening).  We liked the atmosphere of the restaurant.  It felt cozy somehow, though not for lack of space.  Maybe the ceiling was a bit lower than usual.

A very nondescript hole in the wall joint.  We've passed by this place without ever going in.  My friend recommended this place to me.  We walked in just before the dinner crowd and that was a good thing.  Within 15 mins there were tons of people waiting for a table.  

We all got different soups for the chilly night.  I got the hot tofu soup with beef (it was ok, had better at other places), my youngest got the beef dumpling soup (dumpling tasty), and my oldest got the noodle soup with egg (broth was tasty).  They gave us fried fish filet on the house with our ban chan (side dishes).  The one dish almost everyone had was the whole fried chicken.  It was a whole chicken cut up in a tempura batter.  I just wished it had some spice to it, but still really good.  

I'm glad we found a good Korean restaurant not too far from the house.  I'l always craving spicy foods

Because there are not much small tables there, we had to share a big table with another group.

We ordered: 
1. Chicken claws in herbs broth - ok, a lot of broth with only a few pieces of chicken feet, wish there was more.
2. Steamed beef ball - soft, taste the same as other dim sum places.
3. Zhong Shan deep fried roasted pork - the skin not crunchy and meat was a little tough. 
4. Almond fish cake - taste ok and different, warm and fresh from the kitchen.
5. Zhong Shan special dumpling - dough wrapped in a leaf, suppose to be a speciality but failed. The dough was too thick and not much filling.

I was too full and didn't get a chance to try the Fish sui mai, Spareribs with rice roll in claypot, Zhong Shan pork dumplings and the golden sponge cake. It seemed like a lot of tables ordered the claypot and it was a big portion. I'll come back to try next time.

result.name: Club Deluxe: Jazz. Cocktails. Pizza

result.reviews.text: Unfortunately the only good thing I can say is it's a nice room.  However, on a recent Saturday visit we were rather surprised that there was only one bartender and it was obvious that he wasn't happy about it either.  When will businesses learn that presentation is important as soon as you get in the door.  You always want to leave a lasting impression and unfortunately due to rude abrupt bartender, this Canadian won't seek out this place next time visiting the area.

The talent here is ridiculous. Went on a Monday night and it was glorious covers of all top artists and classic songs. Regular bar, noting to write home about. Everyone was there for the musicians. Great date spot.
Cozy nice bar with great local jazz bands caressing your ears and a nice selection of drinks/cocktails.
Nice dive bar for live jazz music in the Haight. I haven't tried the pizza but the cocktails are strong even if they are classic (not the most creative).

Get the Jax pizza: ricotta and meatballs is never a bad choice. I love this place because the pizza is dope and they have live music (mostly jazz) every night. Gotta keep going to live music restaurants and bars so that more would open. SF has so many great musicians; this is one of the few great neighborhood spots for them to perform.

result.adr_address: 1599 Haight St # A, San Francisco, CA 94117-2912, USA
result.formatted_address: 1599 Haight St # A, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Burger Urge

result.reviews.text: This place is great.  They definitely don't skimp on quality.  For all those that left 1 star reviews due to price...their prices are listed right on their gigantic, overhead, menu boards.  If you didn't like the prices...you could have gotten food elsewhere.  Their restrooms are clean and food came out in under 8 minutes for 6 orders.  The yucca fries are awesome!

Horrible. The burgers are SO overpriced, go to Pearls. The girl tried to charge me 20 for a salad. That is INSANE. I watched her add gratuity to the order without me giving it to her as well. Just overpriced and ridiculous
Nice team and atmosphere in this some kind of retro burger restaurant. Perfect for friends night with beer and burgers. Ideally located in SF Haight Ashbury area.
Love the place great food great help thank you thommy
Good burgers, love the fries. A bit costly though. Maybe normal though at SF.

result.adr_address: 1568 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2913, USA
result.formatted_address: 1568 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: HQ Bar & Restaurant

result.reviews.text: Decent food, decent price, located right off of Haight. Surprisingly I went in after work and it was pretty empty. Super friendly staff, I got a "cottage pie" it was basically a Shepard pie, tasted great, and came with a side salad. As someone mentioned there was no ice tea. Does have a full bar.

In the heart of the Haight, this place used to be called "Martin Macks." Nothing has changed on the inside - same food, beer, drinks. Like the food, and have been there many times, by myself and with people. Not a dive like a few of the other bars. Clean bathrooms. Lots of TVs, so don't go there during major soccer or American football unless you want that vibe.
Recently rebranded but not much has changed. It's still great
Great burgers, excellent staff.

Went on a friday afternoon.  Few stools occupied, music playing, otherwise quiet and comfortable.  No Iced tea for beverage, menu short but offered various irish food favorites, the Mack burger and spinach salad were awesome.  The best burger I've ever had, truthfully.  Bacon jam and condiments were perfect.  Very satisfying experience :) Will def go back.

result.adr_address: 1607 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 1607 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Street Taco

result.reviews.text: fast walk-up service and great food! i got the super burrito with chicken-- normally would order carnitas in a burrito but i saw them cooking chicken on the grill and couldn't resist. free chips&salsa.
A little pricey but the food is great. Carne Asada quesadilla was delicious. Tacos were just okay. The line was perpetually out the door.
I go here after work about twice a week. The super burrito is delicious, enough for two mediumish meals, and runs less than $10 by itself. I highly recommend this place.

Best food.  Best service.  Ask to sit with Carlos.  Great Tex-Mex and very diverse crowd - it can feel like a party.  Can get really busy with an after work crowd so you may have to wait.  Powerful margaritas - if you make it past two, you've either really been working out your liver lately or you're likely headed to the floor.  The portions can be huge but there is a great a la carte selection to help with this.

Get anything with Chicken Alambres and your life will forever be changed.  Imagine, a normal chicken burrito/taco/quesadilla, but they throw in grilled peppers, grilled onions, bacon, and cheese for the same price. You're welcome!!

result.adr_address: 1476 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2911, USA
result.formatted_address: 1476 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Crepe Express

result.reviews.text: Very tasty! Quick and nice service... new toppings like strawberries and raspberries (YuMmY) Peaceful music in the background... Great for a short break!
Great service. Handsome, fun and good people in their staff. Great dance skills too. Tasty delicious food. Especially the sweet ones.

Ordered the take out of La Parisiana, crepe with nutella, banana and whipped cream. Was good, served fast. 
Con: The takeout packed as a cone ice cream which was rather inconvenient to carry along with you.
Amazing Crepes that were served to us what felt like seconds after we ordered!! The staff was friendly and they use compostable materials.
A French gentleman served us and was very friendly and helpful. The crepes were delicious! Great experience.

result.adr_address: 1457 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2910, USA
result.formatted_address: 1457 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Panini Cafe

result.reviews.text: Very nice people here - a real community vibe. Coffee is so-so.
Amazing paninis and really nice staff. Best sandwich I've ever had, the Nichole's.
Lovely little shop with decent coffee and great paninis. You could say they live up to their name.
The waiter, I think an English girl, is the rudest person I've ever met in my life. If you don't like to work with people find another job. Won't come back till they change.
Italiano is the best panini I've had, great easy discovery!

result.adr_address: 1451 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2910, USA
result.formatted_address: 1451 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Pork Store Cafe

result.reviews.text: Wow! Excellent food and friendly service. Fair prices. I would highly recommend it for breakfast and lunch.

I'm from Cincinnati and you just don't see Mexican food on the breakfast menu there so it was good to see those dishes are popular in SF. I had the chicken fried steak 1 day and came back again the 2nd day and it did not dissappoint either time. It is very small and since it was just me and my wife we sat at the bar and were seated pretty quickly. Bigger groups would've had a longer wait.

Second time ever in the Haight, this time venturing in for Saturday brunch with a friend. Unlike most other places in the city, the wait at 11am wasn't terrible, at a little under half an hour, though it probably doubled after noon. And, also unlike many other places in the city, they don't have a list to put your names on, so be prepared to actually wait in line the entire time. After settling in, we order:

* Eggs in a Tasty Nest - A little on the salty side, but solid, tasty, and flavorful. Be sure to throw on some hot sauce for that extra oomph!

* Chicken Fried Steak - Honestly, why is this dish named so inconsistently everywhere I go? Sometimes it's country fried, sometimes it's chicken fried. In either case, know that this is NOT chicken, and IS steak. That said, this dish was a bit lackluster. Not bad, but nowhere near as good as what Hard Knox Cafe has to offer.

***Accessibility Info***

Venue - Tiny venue, and, if I recall correctly, only the aisle seating towards the front is really going to be accessible because it's too difficult to navigate towards the back.

Bathroom - Didn't check them out, but if they're in the back, good luck getting over there!
Quality food and service at a great price. Can't get any better than that!

Pretty decent little greasy spoon on Haight Street. Unfortunately (for the locals) it got listed in some guidebook or another, so there is almost always a line of micro-fleece wearing tourists out the door at peak times. If you go on the off times there's almost always room at the counter, though.
  
The patty sausage there is quite good, and the biskets and gravy are wonderful -with a vegetarian gravy option that is just as good as their excellent sausage gravy! Try half and half-hour won't regret it!   
  
The coffee there is ok, but it could certainly be better, given some of the other nearby offerings on The Haight...

result.adr_address: 1466 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2911, USA
result.formatted_address: 1466 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: VeganBurg

result.reviews.text: Holy smokes was this place delicious.  I dragged my two omnivore friends and they were blown away by the specialty burgers. They are both incredibly filling and bursting with wonderful flavor.  A little messy, maybe not a first date joint :) Can't wait for the day we have more of these replacing in and outs!!

Veganburg will quickly become a staple of your diet whether you are vegan, vegetarian OR carnivore!  Their burgers are simply delicious, no matter your protein predilection.

Must haves: The creamy mushroom burger is at the top of my list, along with the "chicken" nuggets.  The french fries are house-made, delicious with simple salt and ketchup.  They offer grilled broccoli as a side, which I must sheepishly admit I prefer over the fries!  Try out their house beverages: they have a very nice selection of teas and lemonades.

The staff is friendly and helpful, and their pride in their food comes through.  Veganburg fits right into its Upper Haight neighborhood.  Their quirky and fun, as well as clean and bright.  Bring a warm layer - it's so cold that sometimes the staff retreats to the back counter.  Avoid parking hassles by taking public transit or catching an Uber.

Vegan food is just the beginning. If you're into burgers, fries and amazing cheesecake, look no further. This place works for vegans and omnis alike. Try the creamy shrooms, cracked Mayo, or any burger on the menu just make sure you add the vegan bacon. You won't regret it. So so good!!!
Holy crap! So good. Great options. Fries were delicious. Burgers were delicious. The soft serve was mind blowing. I want all their food in my mouth.

I really liked the BBQ burger I got. The vegan mayo was not like "real" mayonnaise - I hated mayonnaise but liked this! The blanched broccoli with lemon and olive oil was good.
Nice open airy space.
I like this place!
4 stars because the burgers at not organic.

result.adr_address: 1640 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 1640 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Sparrow Bar and Kitchen

result.reviews.text: The ambiance is the winner here. Service is slow and but the food is good
I'll give this place 4 stars mainly because of stellar service and great atmosphere. The food was ok and it didn't have a full bar. I had the half chicken and it could have used more seasoning.

Did brunch here. Nice ambiance/outdoor seating on a great day. 

Service was attentive and pricing was inline with progressive fare in SF. 

I had the burger which was good (not SF top 5), while others did brunch. Their breakfast was nice. They do a neat homemade sausage.

I came here for lunch recently while on a visit to San Francisco.The place looked respectable and had a clean bathroom so that was a good start.I ordered a grass fed burger for $14 and was told that fries were an extra 2 bucks.....not a good sign.My burger finally came out after over 20 minutes in an almost empty joint at 2pm on a Wednesday.It got worse...the burger had no flavor whatsoever and the fries were stale.I didn't bother to buy a beer because I felt ripped off.After shelling out 21 bucks with tip for a crappy meal I left disgusted.
Great beer, great service, nice our door deck. Happy Hour place to be!

result.adr_address: 1654 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2816, USA
result.formatted_address: 1654 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: El Rancho Grande

result.reviews.text: They stepped their game wayyy up from the previous taqueria that was here. Very extensive and authentic menu (including but definitely not limited to soups, elote, and chilaquiles) with friendly efficient service and normal prices for the city. Maybe not the most slapping Mexican food I've ever eaten, but still five stars compared to the average SF taqueria. I fox with it.
Incredible steak plate. Very generous portions -- most plates could be shared between two people, and a single super taco is a meal all by itself.

result.adr_address: 1428 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2911, USA
result.formatted_address: 1428 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: 1428 Haight Patio Cafe & Crepery

result.reviews.text: We had amazingly good burgers (there's a vegan option or two if I remember correctly). The Patio is a nice place to enjoy your lunch, which was served pretty quick. They have a wide selection of dishes in their menu.

Pros: I love the 1st item on menu...garden fajita crepe.
Dislike: worn booth benches, wobbly tables or too low or too high tables, loud obnoxious 70s music.
GREAT FOOD! Friendly staff, loved the vibe. The price of the food was very very reasonable. great experience all around. Definitely check out the place.
Extremely nice restaurant, kind staff, looks like a small place but has a huge menu. High quality and good free Wi-Fi. Very good food as well
Seriously the Cajun omelet here is the best omelet I've ever had, it's a little spicy but if your OK with that you won't be disappointed. The potatoes are awesome too.

result.adr_address: 1668 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2816, USA
result.formatted_address: 1668 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Om Indian Cuisine

result.reviews.text: For takeout: food was really good, service was quick. Style of food is more creamy and rich (rather than tomato-y or spiced). Don't be afraid to ask for medium spice, the mild had no spice at all.
The food here is very delicious .This is my favourite spot for Indian food and I also like the service provided by them. This is the best spot for Indian food
Excellent food and Good prices. Best naan we've had. Coconut chicken curry was very flavorful.
Delicious and authentic food, paired with great service.
The food is remotely similar to Indian food. Service adequate. Ambience poor.

result.adr_address: 1418 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2911, USA
result.formatted_address: 1418 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Hippie Thai Street Food

result.reviews.text: Yummy Thai food at a good price.  The ambiance is good, but not super high class.  Great for a casual dinner that wont break the bank.

I ordered the lunch special and everything was disgustingly sweet - even the Tom yum soup. Very disappointed with the food as they clearly just pour sugar into everything to cater for every fat Americans tastebuds.

Lunch special comes with salad, soup, appetizer and main course. The Tom Yum soup is simply amazing. Defiantly eat here when you have the chance. Pad Thai comes with meat and tofu. Add your own spicy sauces.

I go to Thailand often as my girlfriend is Thai, this place is very authentic. Also being a vegetarian my level of pickiness is pretty high, they always seem to come correct and are willing to make dishes to your custom order when possible (i.e. No fish sauce, or extra crispy... Etc). Definitely a big step up from the previous Thai spot that was here. My girlfriend grew up on Haight Street and I am a long time local. Although I wish they were still open late at night like before, everything else is way better.l
Food makes you sick and takes forever. I ordered two different things and they came out an hour apart.

result.adr_address: 1671 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 1671 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: DragonEats

result.reviews.text: Best tofu banh mi! Fresh, fast, and filling for only $6. Quality stuff made the way it is supposed to be, and at a good price point. Appreciated the simple menu with vegetarian options. I walked in on a whim and will definitely return .

Good, quick eats.  Less of a restaurant and more like a snack bar.  No tables here.  There are about 6 bar stools to sit against the wall or center island counter.  A little pricey for what you get, but this joint is in a ritzier part of the City.

had Banh Mi with chicken, bread was nicely crusty, also had fresh spring rolls with shrimp; overall food tasted really fresh, they made it to order, if you look for some fresh quick food that fills you up w/o giving you a heavy stomach --> go for it
Highly recommend the 5 spice chicken Bánh mì!
New. Delicious.

result.adr_address: 1398 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 1398 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Magnolia Gastropub and Brewery

result.reviews.text: Great selection of beers on tap, they also have cider.  Good brunch menu and lots of meats and cheeses to enjoy.
I love it here. It's the closest thing I've found to a pub in America. Chilled out, home brews, food, nice staff 👌🏼

I've never had anything but a lovely experience at Magnolia.  I love the space, I love the food, I love the beer.  What else is there?  Oh, yeah, the people who work there.  They're like old friends...and I don't even know them.  :-)

Great place to go drink a beer with friends!! It has a very cool atmosphere, the bar has an underground floor where they produce beer (you can see it through small grids on the bar's floor) so the bar smells of beer making. I myself though the smell was a little weird at first, but you get accostumed to. This is a must go bar if you are visiting San Francisco!! They have a big variety of beers!

Couldn't even get in the door. We wanted to try some of their beers, but drinking only had to sit at the overly packed first come first serve area. There were several spots open for just two people. If I had received this information originally or at least politely, I would have been okay. The girl seating everyone lacked both of these. Will not return.

result.adr_address: 205 Frederick St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 205 Frederick St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Bacon Bacon

result.reviews.text: Sorry, despite the food was fantastic and coffee was good, I came to do a bit of work during my breakfast. The wi-fi kept kicking me out like every few seconds. When I asked staff I was told: "sorry nothing we can do about it, our internet is absolutely terrible, we know it." So now you know as well and can make a qualified decision if you are going in or not.

One of my favorite places in the whole city. Everything on the menu is good. Get the breakfast burrito in the morning or the Cuban sandwich for lunch. Good cam take a little while on weekends, but you can call in an order for carryout.

I had the Bacon and Swiss Croissant sandwich with extra bacon, and it was heaven. My friends all got the pulled pork breakfast burritos, which they absolutely loved. If you want a real special treat, go for the Mexican Hot Chocolate. It might not be on the menu, but it is unbelievably good, and definitely not something to miss. It has marshmallows, bacon, Mexican chocolate, and cinnamon on top. You definitely will not regret a trip here.
Very unique, tasty place!! The fried chicken sandwich was unlike your traditional sandwich...much tastier.  The pork fries are a MUST!! YUM!!

We had breakfast here and ended up sharing a table with the owner. He and the other employees were delightful and it was clear that they really respected each other. The food was delicious and the service was great. I wish I lived in San Francisco so I could eat here daily.

result.adr_address: 1705 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117-2807, USA
result.formatted_address: 1705 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Siam Lotus Thai Cuisine

result.reviews.text: Uneven in its quality. Sometimes it's incredible incredibly flavorful, other times limp and underspiced with dry chicken. The mango chicken is usually a safe bet. The service is very good and the prices are honest.
A Gorgeous place! Food is great and good service with a lot of smiles ))))
they are Decent but i feel they Don't care.. the food was just okay.. and I Happened to be there when the kitchen needed to close early. so we had to get shuffled out.. Bummer :(

All the classic Thai dishes, with the daily specials getting a little more fusion-y or inventive. I love their pumpkin curry and some of the salmon specials. The staff is friendly and the atmosphere is cozy. Definitely my favorite Thai place in the Haight.
The coconut Pad Thai is a very good dish. We also got the Basil Thai and the Pad Thai both of which lacked flavor.

result.adr_address: 1725 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 1725 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Alembic

result.reviews.text: Everyone knows about the killer, creative, cocktails, but the kitchen is the unsung hero of this Upper Haight oasis.   Eclectic play list.   They've recently added a bunch of seating, which is more spacious & quieter than the bar.
An excellent bar with an amazing vibe. Great cocktail selection, experienced barkeepers. We really enjoyed our evening at Alembic.
To hell with the haters: Staff are very friendly, drinks are delicious, and food is brilliant.

Alembic has fancy cocktails, a strong beer list, and *very* tasty sharing-style food. The lighter fare, like the tater tots and lentil croquettes stood out, though the gochujang-glazed ribs were extraordinary too.
The small plates were tasty, small portions (not really to share), a bit on the pricey side. Overall, it was a nice experience. Good cocktails.

result.adr_address: 1727 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 1727 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Burma Bear

result.reviews.text: Our company's catered lunch from Burma Bear was absolutely delicious. The ribs were seasoned perfectly and the tea leaf salad was one of the best I've ever had.
I love their short ribs and coconut rice.
Always seek Burma Bear our at food festivals and events!
Where my hearts real home is

result.adr_address: 1737 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.formatted_address: 1737 Haight St, San Francisco, CA 94117, USA
result.name: Escape From New York Pizza

result.reviews.text: Pretty good pizza, they usually have 5 or 6 different kinds to choose from. It has a nice casual aesthetic and atmosphere. The pizza runs about $4-5 per slice. Slices are perhaps a tad smaller than you'd expect.

Small place a bit dirty NY style with amazing pizzas so good and big. Prefer to take away to watch in front of a football game at home but it is ok to eat "for here". Nice staff, friendly and efficient.

West coast pizza pretty much sucks... There are a few places in the bay are to get a good slice of pizza and escape is one of them. Go in and grab a slice of a standard cheese or pepperoni or try one of the specials of the day... I love the pesto pizza with ricotta or the potato and garlic.... Mmmmmm I want a slice right now. While you are there look at the cool pics of famous people who have also grabbed a slice.
Some pretty good pizza with a decent sized menu. The food was good and the staff was nice.
Escape from the norm and eat here often. I pick up a slice whenever I'm near.

result.formatted_address: 3308 Balboa St, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA

Love the environment here. I suggest getting their Cha Sui Baos (that's the pork buns.)

FOOD:

SERVICE
nice ladies :) I'm glad they open so dang early!!!! 

ATMOSPHERE
Small Chinese dimsum Togo bakery
Good neighborhood feeling. Cakes are just fine.

Came here a couple days ago to get some food for a hike.  Not the best I've ever had, but I always appreciate walking into a Chinese bakery/restaurant where the workers understand and speak English.  Makes the experience that much better.

result.adr_address: 3416 Balboa St, San Francisco, CA 94121-2702, USA
result.formatted_address: 3416 Balboa St, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA
result.name: Chino's Taqueria

result.reviews.text: I remember coming here when I wa in high school at Washington high.  Still great food almost 20 years later.  Try the jumbo burrito.....
Great place to grab a burrito. They slow cook it just like they should authentically. Everything is great here, I've had them all.
Consistently great.  Started to get hard to find parking since the hipsters infested the area.
Great food, Fast. Always get your order exactly how you want it. Prices are more than fair. Great little local spot for fast easy Mexican food.
Mouth watering delicious food.

result.adr_address: 3319 Balboa St, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA
result.formatted_address: 3319 Balboa St, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA
result.name: Shanghai Dumpling King

result.reviews.text:
XLB (Xiao Long Bao) is typically the king of dumplings due to the creative delivery of soup, intense meat and carbs. Like man made cavier the flavor is supposed to burst from within. I've been spoiled with the international king DTF (whaddup Jersey?, Din Tai Fung) in my backyard. It was readily accessible and the gold standard for the item. Chinese food is much better in the Bay that SoCal, so I figured this king delicacy would take XLB to the next level. I was not deterred by a neighborhood spot. It has 2K+ reviews and a line out the door.

Man cannot live off of XLB alone, despite my efforts to do just that. Those bad boys take time to pinch closed and a few order takes quite a few minutes. The place is cramped, smaller than a garage with everyone from college kids to lounging families and out of towners basking in it's glory. Service is pretty spotty and they know it, but they don't care. Their food is good and they know it and one honest review isn't going to change that and it shouldn't deter you from coming, just be prepared. Décor is basic af and despite the free tea at each table when you sit down, the tea is forgettable. You'll notice a slight grime because I'm skeptical as to the cleaning practices between tables, that rag looks might shared to me if you know what I'm saying. Price is cheap, you can eat on a Jackson and get a variety of items. Sodas from the can and waters do not come with ice. 

Crispy green beans are legit, probably one of the best things on their menu, yeah that's right a vegetarian item slays the hardest. Bright, green, crunchy, salty (probably MSG, but at this point who cares, MSG was so 90's, at least it's gluten free, amiright?), garlics to boot. Throw some sambal hot chili sauce and your good to go. Already overdosed on rice this far we decided that the crispy onion pancakes would give us the starch part of the meal. Could do without as the green onion was barely noticeable. 

XLB's came late and had the weakest bottoms. I'm good at handling them, but ¼ of the first order almost broke so I changed it up with the scoop technique which I only have to use in inferior dumplings. The bright burst of flavor was not there, the dough was very prevalent and thick. Felt more like overcooked pasta than, hand closed dumplings. The inside meat ratio was off, too little soup, too much meat and it wasn't even that good. Average at best. The vinegar was only ok, they didn't have sesame seed oil with it and the ginger at the bottom did not seem fresh and bright. This made it difficult to give it the proper cooling bath.

Spicy wontons were a welcome pleasure. The sauce had hints of peanuts so it reminded me of a kare kare Filipino dish, but the balance of the saltyness came from the meat, well made wontons held up nicely. This was a very complete item and easily something that should be sought over the XLB, weird to say, maybe I got a bad 2 batches, but this and the green beans were the stars here. Steamed buns were small, well portioned and perfect.

Trying to flag down a staff member is like pulling teeth for napkins, water refills, our initial drink order and even when they forgot out XLB's. The food is good, they deliver, but hours and service suck.

Delicious and reasonably priced! Favorites include the garlic pea sprouts, soup dumplings, and this fluffy egg pastry for dessert (can't remember what it's called). Definitely gets crowded, so they'll take your order while you're waiting so the food is pretty much ready when you're seated - efficient! Cash only.

I ate there a few times. The dumplings are not as good as the review wrote about. The last time my family and I were there, the dumplings we ordered are under cooked/steamed. I told the waiter about it and he said it's already cooked. And I didn't believe him. So we ended up did not finish the dumplings. After an hour later, I had stomach reaction/pain. The meat/stuffing inside the dumplings was mushy and so soft. Could not taste the meat at all.
Dumplings are great, soups are good, BYOB...but service is spotty. I suppose they just want to get everyone in and out, so dont expect the most courteous service.
One of San Francisco's best kept secret restaurants. Hands-down the best dumplings in SF. Try the Spicy Shrimp dumplings that are not on the menu. You will thank me later!

result.adr_address: 3420 Balboa St, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA
result.formatted_address: 3420 Balboa St, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA
result.name: Sapoten‎

result.reviews.text: Amazing hand rolls and unique sashimi. Must try: spicy tuna hand roll, spicy scallop hand roll, "pumpkin" sashimi.

a little neighborhood restaurant in the outer Richmond. super cozy place a bit away (actually it's not only "a bit." imagine how far balboa theatre is from downtown) I went there Sunday early evening. 2 customers and of course I didn't need to wait to be seated. the server, she is adorable. a bit robot-like but that's her charm. I ordered kamikaze sushi roll and miso ramen. sushi roll is decent. looks yummy. fish is fresh and spicy tuna inside is not too spicy. perfect much of spicy. I actually got 2nd one. still good. I wasn't WOW for miso ramen tho. taste ok but it's more taste like shio (oriental or salt based it's called?) ramen than miso ramen. ramen is just ok. but next time I'll try saba shioyaki or tempura, those entrèe. one thing. there are pictures on the wall. bunch of girls wearing kimono. I'm pretty much sure it's Japanese version of disney princesses. good. recommended
Pretty good.
Amazing sushi for price, noodles were only ok, best service in SF

TLDR: Okay sushi (not bad), but subpar service.

Service was.. apathetic throughout our dinner. When we were ordering, she didn't even write down our items (AGAIN, which is completely fine), but she just had a dead look on her face and didn't even nod or repeat the order to us, and at the end (here's the kicker), was just like, "That's it?" Guuuuuuurl. No smiles, no checking in on us, had to ask for tea/water.

Food: is not BAD and okay for the price. Everything we had was, again, just okay - they didn't overdo it on the rice and the amount of fish they used in their sushi was fair. Like someone else said, it's about two notches above buffet sushi - the grade of fish is not the freshest but it's not the worst either. One of their saving graces was that their avocado was fresh and they didn't skimp on that.

I could see this as a convenient spot if you live in the Outer Richmond, or have a Groupon, and just want to satisfy your sushi craving but definitely not somewhere to go out of your way for.

result.reviews.text: Very nice people. The food is good & while the prices are fair [similar to downtown & mission st. bistro's], it's perhaps a little high for Balboa st. & the outer Richmond dist. It's a fairly small room, painted in blue, with two large murals : sort of 'cold', esp. when they keep the front door open [as they often do].  A nice variety of sandwich's & breakfast's...They no longer make their own pastries, but have the standard muffins & bagels, etc [nice when heated] & their coffee is better than average ...A nice addition to the Balboa st. area....Between three & a half & four stars.....

Let me break it down in very simple terms:
1. it's a locally owned neighborhood cafe run by some really nice people
2. everything is homemade and fresh
3. it's a short walk to and from the beach with plenty of street parking
4. while I really liked my greek salad, the others with me were not happy
5. a $9 sandwich is nothing more than two pieces of bread, no sides
6. the place is a bit pricey 
7. it is very homey and comfortable 
Would I go back for lunch, probably not, but would I stop for a cup of coffee.
Service awesome, food delicious, friendly people and great location.

This newly opened family run cafe is a great addition to the area. Having had both their breakfast & lunch sandwiches plus beverages recently all were very delicious and reasonably priced. Especially like the comfy (overstuffed) seating available, but keep in mind that there is a limited about in this small yet charming cafe. Cherubs as a focal for the decor is a nice touch. result.reviews.text: Cassava is a terrific neighborhood spot offering delicious food with local ingredients and a friendly atmosphere. Their food is always on point and really flavorful. They also collaborate with the Balboa Theater to offer a 3 course menu for those watching a movie on Thursdays.

*** In Short ***

Brunch. Cute. Tasty. Takes reservations. Need I really say more? Okay, fine: if they have it, be sure to try the Merguez lamb sausage.

*** In Depth ***

My friend, who absolutely loves Cassava, has been telling me she wants to take me here since, oh, my birthday last year? So, after more than a year, I decided to just go myself, with a different friend. Oops.

Anyway, I ordered their:

* Merguez Lamb Sausage - This was just divine. Flavorful? Yup. Rich? Oh, definitely. Greasy? Very much so. Delicious? Hells yeah. 

* Braised Short Rib "Hash" - Not so much a hash as it was a quinoa and potato bowl topped with a poached egg and fall off the bone tender rib deliciousness.

Cute little brunch spot, with a simple, but fantastic color scheme, and a combination of indoor and outdoor seating. Oh, and my favorite part? They take reservations. For brunch. WIN!

***Accessibility Info***

Venue - We were seated on the border of their in/outdoor seating, so I didn't pay too much attention to the interior seating arrangement. If memory serves me, I remember the place being a little on the smaller side, with the border seating actually being the best option. That said, my end of the table was on a slight decline backwards, which made for slightly awkward seating. 

Bathroom - Didn't try.

Great food with diverse culinary backgrounds. I enjoy the food both as a fine taste and as an art, even. I've had a couple meals before; most recently, I had the Mr & Mrs Croque sandwich, bread and contents toasted together in a coherent yet fluid sensation. Highly recommend if nearby.

I had just landed in San Francisco an hour before me and my friend (from Vancouver) ate here -- we were extremely hungry. We were staying in the Richmond District so we quickly yelped breakfast spots around the neighbourhood where we could walk to; Cassava was recommended. 

When we got there, I spent at least 10 minutes deciding against their brunch menu or the Randwich. I asked the server which one she liked better and she told me that the Randwich was a messy favourite. She did not lie. 

With my last name also being "Rand", I truly feel like my life changed after eating this sandwich. I took an uber home from the bar later that evening and was told that I spent 15 minutes drunk-explaining my love for this sandwich. It's THAT good. 

10/10 Recommend.

Great Japanese style breakfast.
Good prices for quality and portions.
Odd hours makes it difficult to not plan to eat here, but hey, it's worth the plan.

result.reviews.text: TERRIBLE Service. I usually don't ever post a review on yelp, but this was so bad I had to. I went here for the first time and it will be my LAST. The waiter didn't even ask what I wanted to drink. So I ate my entire meal with NO water. He never not once asked how the food is tasting or if he can get me anything else. I had to stand up and ask for a to go box. I didn't even get an itemized receipt. So the receipt did not even reflect what I ordered. It was just a receipt with the amount. THEN THE WAITER HAD THE AUDACITY TO FINALLY COME UP TO MY TABLE AND THE FIRST THING HE DID WAS LOOK AT MY TAB TO SEE IF THERE WAS A TIP. THEN HE SAID, NO TIP?? I was like wooowwwww. just wow.  This is why people think asian restaurants have terrible service everywhere, because of people like this. The food was good but not enough for me to go there ever again.

This was a good place. Definitely not your Americanized Chinese food. I've never been directed to "real" Chinese food before but I was impressed with the food as it was. 

A lower rating is given due to the fact the table they gave us had other dishes on it and they just rearranged the stuff on the table to the next table. The restrooms were not great. Only one men's and it was some what of a hole feeling. The service lacked on refilling drinks because the whole restaurant sat down to eat lunch together about 230 pm in the middle of the dining room.
OK food let down by sloooooow service.

This is a tough rating. If you know what you're getting, it's great. If not, you may be disappointed. 
The eating area was pretty clean, although they had set dirty dishes and things on the table they sat us at and they moved them without bringing new things to set the table......little sketchy with the cleanliness there. The bathroom wasn't terribly clean either. 
As for the food, it took some getting used to. I have never had "real" Asian/Chinese food before, but from what I've had explained, this us what I imagine. It's not Americanized Asian food. It is more simple, a little bland, fewer ingredients than what American food has. But it's got flavor if you can learn to like it quick, or if that's your taste. 
The menu was tough for me. There are many choices and they are not described much. It basically just lists what it is, sometimes that is fairly self explanatory, sometimes it's not.
Prices are reasonable. Food is okay but service can be improved.

result.reviews.text:
Great fresh noodles with awesome texture. Large portions and fair prices make it a great choice for Xi'an tastes. 

We tried the main-pi with sesame - these are thick, cold noodles with an oily chili sesame sauce. If you like sesame these are really good! 

The noodles in sizzling oil were also good, it's a simple mostly  noodle and bean sprout bowl with a big pile of spice on top (I'd guess cumin, chilli, and a few others). You mix it all together and you end up with a flavorful, fairly spicy bowl of nicely chewy noodles. I would have appreciated slightly more oil in this one though. 

Last, we had the qishan minced pork noodles. These were probably the winning dish (but all were good). Delicious thick noodles in a rich, hearty soup. 

Attentive service despite being very busy. Its between a 4 and a 5, but as a noodle lover I'm bumping it up. Highly recommended.

Purely rating on the hand-cut noodles which was very tasty.  The texture had the right amount of chewiness.  The service is good.  I saw some other tables order the bao stuffed with meat, we figured out later it was the "hambuger" on the menu.  I couldn't figure out what some of the items on the menu is because of the vague description.
Get the shaanxi mian-pi, biang biang noodles, and some cold appetizers. You can easily spend under $15 per person here if you come with a group and feel satiated!

I've been here several times.  They just reopened under new management.  Slightly new menu, but happy they kept my favorites.  A little more expensive now, taste is a little different but overall still good.  Ordered lamb dumplings with chili sauce, and Braised chicken and potatoes with their hand cut noodles.

result.adr_address: 2652 Judah St, San Francisco, CA 94122-1432, USA
result.formatted_address: 2652 Judah St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: The Pot's

result.reviews.text:
The Pot's makes for a fun, delicious meal with friends. It's all-you-can-eat hot pot. They have so many items, everything from plain and marinated meats (lamb, pork, beef, seafood) to seafood (tilapia, shrimp), and veggies. They also have a wide variety of noodles and dumplings. I wasn't a fan of the shrimp paste or Shanghai Pork Dumpling (XLB). That kind of dumpling is not meant for hot pot. Come with a group so you can order everything! The portion size of each order is pretty big. You are guaranteed to get food coma.

One negative is that they don't have many sauces. The hot pot restaurants back home in MD and VA have a full sauce bar allowing you to make your own tasty concoctions. I guess they make up for that with their many soup options. If you get more than one soup base, it's an additional $1 per person. Definitely worth it! We went with the Pork Bone and Spicy Miso.

All the hotpot!  Was tasty, and wait staff was very efficient, readily getting everything we might need.

Came here for a large group dinner, 20 of us, and we had no problems getting the reservations, and we never ran low on delicious hot pot.
I really like this place alot. It's busy sometimes but service is still great

My best friend and I come here a lot every time he comes back from college. It is definitely one of the more AFFORDABLE hot pot places in the city. I would definitely recommend this place if you cannot afford to pay like $25+ for hot pot. The stuff here is really good, it is rarely ever crowded. I recommend the porkbone for the soup. and their menu is actually quite extensive. Prime rib beef, lamb, beef marinated in wine, and a wide assortment of other foods available that are not at other places.

This place has a great selection of different broths and ingredients for their Chinese style hot pots.  The service is a bit slow, but it's all you can eat and they don't rush you here.  The beef is pretty good, but the lamb came out with some freezer burn on it.  There's a wide variety of seafood, vegetables, and marinated meats as well.  If you're coming hungry, you can definitely get your money's worth here for about $30 a head after taxes!

result.adr_address: 2225 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.formatted_address: 2225 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: Marnee Thai Restaurant

result.reviews.text: You can find tasty super authentic dishes here that you won't find anywhere else. Don't miss the hotcakes or the sea bass with garlic and pepper. The northern Thai tea leaf salad is quite good. It's on par with the other Burmese restaurants around; however, we were kind of hoping for something more unique.

Delicious food at a great price. Appetizers can be a little pricy but I still felt everything was worth it. The avocado salad with soft shell crab was delicious. The pad see ew was also great. 

Service was fast and efficient and coming in at 6pm on a Saturday with very little wait time.

The panang beef curry was totally tasteless, probably the worst curry I ever had in a Thai restaurant. The pot stickers in spicy green curry sauce were very good. Prices are high compared to other Thai restaurants, and service is only average.

A quaint and homey feeling thai restaurant who's kitchen packs a wide variety of flavors into very elegant and enjoyable dishes. I would eat here again, and would definitely recommend to friends if they were in the area

Food is only mediocre for Thai food. Nothing really stands out. The service you get here also depends on what you are. As Asian, I get treated like a nobody while other folks get the "nice" treatment. I'm tired of restaurant service that behave this way. Next time I see that, I will leave a lousy tip because they already expect that from us. YMMV.

result.adr_address: 2250 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.formatted_address: 2250 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: TeaWay

result.reviews.text:
I have to say, Teaway was so much better when its first Irving Street store opened in 2009. The current Teaway has been under different management. I still enjoy the self-serving part of putting toppings in my own cup. The staff is generally friendly. Only if they can be more accurate in taking orders (e.g. when customer asks for "no ice", make sure to not put any ice).  

The drinks are still decently priced; taste not bad, but not that great either. The snacks quality seem to be inconsistent--on some days they could taste really good; on others, hard to chew.
They have a great variety of boba tea. The prices are moderate.
This place makes me get diaherria. Last time I went to this place was 3 years ago. Their drinks has been made days ago and left in the fridge.
Last man standing, formally one of 3 within 2 blocks of each other. The primary party trick of this place is your personal addition of toppings.

This place is decent if you order bubble tea, but not if you want anything else. They technically have iced mocha on their menu, but they don't understand what a mocha actually is. What they'll give you is a coffee flavored milk tea, when it's supposed to be an espresso with milk + chocolate. Their milkshakes aren't milkshakes neither; what they make is watery and not thick.

tl;dr They'll make any drink like a milk tea, so you shouldn't order anything but milk tea from them.

result.adr_address: 2240 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.formatted_address: 2240 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: Saiwaii Ramen

result.reviews.text: Disclaimer: I am a ramen virgin and my knowledge of what good vs amazing ramen it's almost non-existant. All I knew was that I wanted to try tonkotsu ramen first. I chose Saiwaii only because of it's hours and proximity to my visit to SF. I ordered the Spicy Garlic Tonkotsu lunch special which came with a 6 piece sushi roll; I opted for a Sake Avocado Roll. The service was amazingly fast with both items at the table in a matter of minutes. The sushi was OK, a bit small but it was only $2 more than the ramen alone. The tonkotsu was very delicious, not too spicy and just the right size. Although I was very satisfied with my meal, I the feeling that tonkotsu might be much better elsewhere. I will try a few more places as my visits to SF allow.

The ramen soups are descent. The sushi is ok and too expensive for the quality being served. The ramen soups is what I would go for in this place, nothing else, as they are priced appropriately for the quality of the food in this restaurant. I like the local and unpretentious neighborhood atmosphere here, and I probably come once every 3 months.

Delicious ramen!! Very fast and friendly service. I eat ramen all over the city and one thing I've noticed is that some places give you egg, mushroom and spinach or some combo of these included in the price. Here I had to pay a dollar for the egg, which is common.

But over all really good food and nice people. It was pretty easy to park and walk here and even though they were packed, with a wait, I was sat within 5 minutes, order taken in two, answering all my questions patiently and good arrived about 5 minutes later. From parked to food in my face in 15 minutes. Wow!!!

One of my favorite Ramen places in San Francisco, they have a good selection of different broths that all taste good. Their sushi is also always fresh and taste really good as well. There is typically a line since the place isn't so big but it's worth the wait in my opinion.
Great food! Love their selection of appetizers. Can't go wrong with the spicy garlic ramen. Expect to wait at least 15-20 minutes for a table.

result.formatted_address: 1851 Noriega St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: L'Chaim Sushi

result.formatted_address: 2240 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
