result.adr_address: 2228 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122-1619, USA
result.formatted_address: 2228 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: Loi's Vietnamese Restaurant

result.reviews.text: I've been here several times and love their food as well as their prices. Brought my friend last week and he loved the egg rolls so much we ordered two. The beef stew over rice is my go to meal. The owners are very friendly and welcoming.

I was here over a year ago and I still rave about this place to my friends. I've eaten a LOT of pho over the years and this place is amazing. At least, it was  on the day I ate there. Basil was a little dry but, to be honest, I throw so much of it in that I don't really care. The broth was perfect and the seared beef was delicious. I have zero qualms about encouraging people to give it a try and remember, this is not a commercial eatery so don't expect this to have a chain restaurants atmosphere and service detail.

This is the worst place I have been to in a long time. Stay away or eat here at your own risk!

Service: not existing at all! The server is Super  rude older gentleman. 
Atmosphere: place is very dirty and old inside. 
Food: I found a piece of burned and melded plastic in my pork. I tasted funny so, I looked closely and here it was! 

The other option if you feeling risky is to go Skydiving at Lodi Parachute Center and if you really want good and affordable Pho head up 2 blocks on Irving and go to Kevin's Noodle House.
The most amazing bbq beef ever. Sometimes I just skip the soup and get beef dishes straight. The space can be a little cramped.

Talk about rude. The older man that works here harasses me because we're sharing a dish and isn't content with us doing so(there's three of us, we ordered two dinners and one appetizer). After I decline to order more, he scoffs at me. What the heck? They burnt the crap out of our appetizer, too. Exercise caution when coming here, the place has some questionable customer service. Not coming back.

result.adr_address: 1755 Noriega St, San Francisco, CA 94122-4307, USA
result.formatted_address: 1755 Noriega St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: Noriega Teriyaki House

result.reviews.text: I love these guys' soft shell crab appetizer.  The nigiri sushi is great too. Fish is always very fresh.  I do think their sushi boats have a bunch of "filler" maki pieces, but for the price it's not bad.  Service is good.

My aunt and uncle invited me out to join them for lunch with some of my other relatives. Since they all ordered cooked food, I thought maybe I should be different and order something with raw fish so I got the chirashi. 

For the price, the chirashi had a pretty good portion size and variety of seafood. The regular fishes like salmon and tuna were fine. The tuna looked a little washed out, but it still tasted ok. The best part was a plump, shimmering piece of hotate, which was sweet and succulent. Some things could use some improvement though. I think there was a piece of tai that was oddly spongy. Maybe it spent too much time in the freezer. The saba was also pretty rough and chalky, and the rice was too sweet and was covered with some weird pickled vegetables. It was far from perfect, but you can't really expect a place like this to be super stellar.

The hot food seemed to be better than the raw fish. I tried the beef teriyaki, and it wasn't bad. I guess it's hard to go wrong with grilled meat. It had a good sear and was tender enough. They used too much of the generic, sweet teriyaki sauce, but it still tasted ok. Other people seemed to like the tempura and salmon teriyaki entrees as well. This stuff isn't exactly super authentic or special, but they seem to make it better than the other items on the menu. 

Noriega Teriyaki is fine as a local place, but I don't think anyone would go out of their way to come here.
This place is pretty good. The tea is great and the rolls are good. It is a very nice place to take kids and is in all pretty relax and casual. The service is good and fast.

Used to work near here and would dine in occasionally only to celebrate when a coworker was leaving us for greener pastures.  Friendly service.  Generous lunch portions, but a little pricey compared to the Chinese BBQ & noodle joint down the same block.  Worth it for the infrequent special occasion.
Service is fast and the food is good for the price. If you get the tempura udon be sure to get the tempura ok the side or else you'll have really nasty soggy udon. The tea here is really good too.

result.adr_address: 2218 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122-1619, USA
result.formatted_address: 2218 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: Bei Fang Style

result.reviews.text: Huge plates of dumplings, they were better than the beef noodle soup (a little bland).  Also tried the pork buns which were ok.  I'd come back for the dumplings.

result.formatted_address: 2191 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA

result.adr_address: 2222 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.formatted_address: 2222 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: T C Pastry

result.reviews.text: I used to live around the corner, and will stop by whenever in the city. Reliably good bang for the buck dim sum.
Excellent, great value, tasty Dim Sum!  The shrimp with cilantro and shrimp with chives are awesome!

Great small dim sum (not the cart kind) and dumpling store in Sunset. Decor is nothing to speak of, they just offer tasty food items here. Order at the cash register, and pickup when they call your name. Love the dumplings (Pork BBW, ahhhhh), sesame balls, potstickers, etc. Take out is an option here (likely the default for most sales it seems).

breakfast items are good for a quick to go dimsum before you start your day. 

a hole in the wall, but well worth it

Best take-out dim sum on this side of GG Park. 

The set-up is a bit different than others in the sense that you aren't pinned against a long counter and people try to enter and exit like other dim sum spots. The counter here is in the back, and many of the items have one display piece and then the ladies grab the fresh stuff from steamers in the back. Also, I find that this place, by far, has the nicest staff--a big plus in these grab and go places!

Their strong points are some of the hot items like the jooks, fried wonton for days when you need something crispy and deep fried, and black sesame soup. Their steamed buns are delicious and fluffy (3 per order) and their cheung fun (filled rice noodle) are great for a carb blast. I love the bitter melon and chicken because it makes me feel like I'm being healthy. Overall a great place to stop in and grab a quick meal or snacks. There are a few basic tables inside, otherwise the ladies pack up the food well.

Tip: they have an end of day fire sale where remaining items are discounted, so it's even cheaper to get your eats on!

result.adr_address: 2191 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.formatted_address: 2191 Irving St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA
result.name: Guangdong Barbecue Tea House

result.reviews.text:
We didn't order any Chinese roasted meats here, but I heard it's not as good as Ming Kee's. My parents and I just had a casual dinner here, and it was ok.

Apparently, the staff from Mayflower on Geary moved here after it closed. Mayflower was very adept at making Cantonese broths, and it's still pretty tasty here. The Soup of the Day (Lai Tong) had a pretty developed flavor. There was a good amount of pork, veggies, dates, and other Chinese ingredients I don't know the English names of. It may not be as refined as Mayflower's, but it was still pretty good. 

The Clear Broth Beef Brisket (Ching Tong Ngau Lam) was so-so. The brisket was tender, but it wasn't that flavorful. The broth also needed more anise or other spices for some more depth. I also thought that it had too much Chinese pickles in it that gave it more of a briny flavor. Ever since Harbor Village in the Embarcadero shut down, I don't think I've come across a good version of this dish in the States.

Our last dish was Stir Fried Cod Fillet. There was a good amount of fish pieces, but they were also pretty bland. Bonus points for yellow chives, but it still needed to be more aromatic. There was lots of broccoli so at least it's healthy I guess.

Dessert was Red Bean Soup. My mom loves the stuff, but I can't stand the overpowering flavor of the dried orange peel. If that's your thing, knock yourself out.
The food is good but it's too greasy. But I guess that's what I should expect from a Chinese BBQ restaurant. Service is good. People who work there are pretty friendly.

I like their dead animal bbq hanging from the front window.  The cherry duck hanging out, dripping fat and slow cooked to perfection and dont forget about the fatty char sui (bbq glazed pork).  You can thank me later!

great for a quick lunch!

classic items, and amazing flavors.

Very Good Food and Service.
This small cafe has the best, authentic Chinese Food. A little intimidating walking past the hanging fowl and pork, and sometimes difficult getting past the language barrier. BUT, we have had chinese foods all over Nor Cal and we do not miss the opportunity to dine here.
Do stray from the typical fare offered at your neighborhood restaurant and experience what chinese food is all about.
Particularly good duck, salt and pepper calimari (appetizer), the pork and eggplant. It's impossible to choose favorites, NEVER have we been dissatisfied.

result.adr_address: 2120 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123-2756, USA
result.formatted_address: 2120 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Lucca Delicatessen

result.reviews.text:
I just moved to the Marina and was excited to find this deli. However, after frequenting a few times I've decided that I will not be patronizing this establishment anymore. Here's why:

The first time I visited Lucca's, I purchased 2 containers of olives, a jar of tiny pickled peaches (at least I think that's what they are), and a hunk of cheese. I was charged $45. I went ahead an paid for it, feeling like it was quite a lot for 4 things, and so I asked for an itemized receipt. Turns out I was charged twice for everything. It was a young man who did it and he didn't seem apologetic. His co-worker (young, slightly heavyset man) apologized casually and gave me money back in cash (though it was still a little short - I had paid with credit card).

I thought maybe it was an honest mistake so I kept going back. Two times I had success, with a nice older man who I assume might be the owner or manager. So I thought, yay! I found my neighborhood deli!

The last time I went there, it was the same young man who overcharged me the first time. This time, he ran me up for a loaf of bread and a few other things. I asked him how much the bread was. He paused, and said...7.99. 

This was a loaf of bread from a local maker that I know doesn't cost that much. It was a small loaf. Anyway, I just felt like this was getting ridiculous. Obviously this guy does this a lot, overcharges and pockets the cash.

So until this guy is fired or something, I am not going to go to Lucca's anymore. Too bad because it is close and convenient for me.

this is an old school classic italian deli the locals all know and love the space is cramped and there only a bench out front to eat at but the food is solid. If your planning a party or are cooking italian come here and shop you will not be dissapointed your taste buds will thank you

Lucca's is a great old-school Italian deli serving fresh deli sandwiched.  We stopped in to pick up lunch for a picnic at the nearby park.  The place is tiny (no place to est inside, only park benches on the sidewalk outside). Got the mufaletta, meatball, and vegie sandwiches. Growing up on the true New Orleans mufaletta, i was preparing myself to be let down but Lucca's version was impressive.  The meats and cheeses were sliced to order, the olive salad was spot on, and they added enough olive oil to round out the taste.  The only real difference was the bread which is traditionally a round seeded loaf.  No big deal.  The sandwich was great.  The meatballs sandwich was also tasty.  The meatballs themselves were tender and well seasoned and the marinara sauce was also good.  The vegie sandwich was a vegie sandwich...  Go to Lucca's.
Great little place to grab a sandwich and eat it on the go. Lots of readymade stuff to grab and go.

This place gets pretty busy for the lunch hour. Thankfully they have an online ordering system so all you have to do is pop by and pick it up. I would say sandwiches could be a little bigger for the price especially vs somewhere like Golden Gate Market nearby.
Nevertheless, sandwiches were on point, ordering was quick and easy, and despite being super busy, service was very friendly. Parking is what it always is but if you're picking up a to-go order, definitely bring a buddy to run in and grab the food to make things go smoother.

The menu is also pretty large and I can definitely see myself coming back to try all that they offer as the location is pretty conveniently near the office.

result.adr_address: 2084 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123-2735, USA
result.formatted_address: 2084 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Naked Fish

result.reviews.text: Great place for Sushi recommended by my grand daughter.Different rolls and all are tasty!

So many inventive rolls that were all so tasty. My husband and I came here for a date night after I returned from a month abroad and it was so wonderful. I'm glad this was the first sushi I had after coming home!
Lunch special is very reasonable here! Less than 9 dollars for California roll and Saba shioyaki.
Great food, great service, and reasonable prices.  Loved it!

I went here for happy hour with my roommate before we went off to our respective events.  The happy hour menu is an extensive one compared to other menus I've seen at sushi restaurants.  And the prices were really good too.

I ordered the crunchy cannon roll, which was $6 (normally $8).  It was really delicious!  It was fried to perfection, and the honey mustard and unagi glaze gave it sweetness.  I can predict that some people might find this signature roll too sweet, but I enjoyed it.  What I also like was that they didn't skimp on the portion.  I got about 10 pieces, which didn't make me full, especially since I also ordered ahi poke.  Which, btw, was also very good.  It came with wontons, and added a salty flavor to this acidic dish.

The atmosphere is dark, and it can get loud inside.  The wait staff are really friendly and are happy to answer any questions you have.

I would definitely come back here and take advantage of their happy hour menu.  You get the best of what they offer at a good price, especially for the Marina.

result.adr_address: 2142 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 2142 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Dragon Well

result.reviews.text: Excellent chinese cuisine including a large gluten-free menu. My partner is a celiac and has never had any problems when eating here. Our favorite dining in San Francisco, and that's saying a lot!
food is great but amount of food is not that large and expensive
Nice food, service and ambience. Would definitely visit it again!

Excellent find! Somewhat of a hole in the wall; a long skinny restaurant often lost in the plethora of restaurants on Chestnut Street. I stumbled upon it 1.5 years after living 6 blocks away, and loved it. I had the duck in steamed rolls appetizer and it melted in my mouth. Quick service, good food; all around win.
Horrible service. Came in and hostess (or waiter) showed us table, so we went there, but after couple minutes woman went out and very rough asked us move to different table.

result.adr_address: 2150 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 2150 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Blackwood

result.reviews.text: Excellent breakfast. Their specialty bacon is interesting: thick and savoury, with a sweet curing. Fluffy eggs, tasty potatoes and fresh salad and fruits. Only "drawback": the portions are HUGE. The decor of the place is  interesting as well: lots of glass, high ceilings and a hint of brutalism. Last note: the service was PERFECT. Attentive, polite and very very quick. We'll be back.

Been here multiple times and although the food is great their service is terrible. They can't manage a queue. Although there's a sign-up sheet the hostess (who seems to have trouble understanding spoken English) has, in more than one occasion, sat parties of the same size before me without even calling out the names listed. This was the last time I come to Blackwood after being a costumer here for 2 years. Keep up the good work.

Scored brunch here over the weekend without any waits. Ended up ordering two eggs with the chicken mango sausage while friends ordered a combination of dishes including the millionaire bacon. My food was great and would happily come back again. The bacon is certainly good, but consider it as a side.

Another nice place ruined by the lemmings. Seatng too close to other people and WAY TOO NOISY. Bottomless mimosas add to the bad atmosphere. Rude customers letting phones ring loud and saying "hello?" really loud. 
I don't like their spaghetti noodle decoration on EVERY DISH. their dry unbuttered toast. Their messy smelly (mold) bathroom. Messy, wet floor, crowded walkway dining room to bathroom. Mismanaged.
Pricy and noisy, but has a really nice location on the pier. Good place to meet up with friends, grab a quick drink, and wander the piers.

result.adr_address: 2105 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 2105 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Blue Barn Gourmet

result.reviews.text: Nice high end sandwich and salad place. Sustainable, organic ingredients. Very yummy. A little pricey but not outrageous. I had their spicy tuna salad ($15) and it was delicious.

Found my store! Big salads! 
Disliked their convoluted menu. Also sandwich menu hidden
Awesome quick lunch, great deli sandwich, in and out in five minutes.

Best takeout salads in SF and some of the best sandwiches as well (the rooster is excellent). More expensive than some alternatives, but blue barn gets all the details right. Extremely fresh (and local) ingredients, perfect balance of flavors, and just the right amount of dressing. 

There will be lines. You will wait longer than you want for your food. You'll pay a few extra bucks for your salad/sando. Be patient... Or if the few extra bucks and/or the wait is too much to handle, then walk a couple blocks down the street to settle for shmeh at Plutos, where you can get a cheaper, more mediocre salad.
We tried a salad and a sandwich, both were delicious. Fast service and friendly people.

result.adr_address: 2066 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 2066 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Le Marais Bakery

result.reviews.text: Food is definitely tasty, although a tad pricy. Sadly the owner is skimpy on the service: for alkost 50 seated places there is only one waitress. When we were there, at the tail end of rush hour on a weekday morning, she was overwhelmed and couldn't keep up. Always polite, but we had to wait a long time.

I wanted to like this shop.  It's so cute and the pastries looked so good.  The beignet I got was burnt.  You couldn't see that it was burnt because they covered it with chocolate.  It wasn't even a proper beignet, it was more of a really dried donut with not so great cream filing.

The baked goods look good but i couldn't get any service as I admired them at the counter. It was not busy. At least 3 staff were near me but ignored.  I saw the sign "be seated" and asked staff person ok I sit outside. She boringly said, "how many?" I said 1 and she didn't direct me to a table and ignored initial question about sitting outside. I asked if ok I sat at a particular inside table and she ignored These people are burnt out! She pointed to where the menus were (I hadnt asked) and when i went to where she pointed i didn't see any. Another staff person was seated nearby and I asked her where they were, and she glumly grabbed 1 (1 sheet of flimsy dirty crumpled white paper) and brusquely said "we're out of French toast and quiche". I took menu and sat down and no one came to me. The few patrons had already been served or eaten. The 3 staff weren't doing anything. This was 2:30 pm Sat.
The menu was hard to read.
I just wanted a pasty and coffee.
No server came.
I walked.
S... hole.
Avoid

Just the absolute worst customer service in SF. Get your coffee and croissant elsewhere. Rude, disrespectful staff. Their food certainly can't justify their attitude. Hopefully something else will replace them soon as this seems to be the theme of their reviews.
Stopped in after completing the 415k 12k run. Good coffee and delicious beignet (Raspberry filled). It would have been nice to have a larger size coffee choice, but what I got was good.

result.adr_address: 2095 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 2095 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Glaze Teriyaki

result.reviews.text:
Very good place, the food is amazing (for a French in the US it's rare to say it) 

The staff is nice and helpful! 

I recomand it !
Finally, healthy quick food for fitness conscious food lovers.
While my friend complained of her food not being warm, mine on the other hand was just right .
Chicken, steak, brown rice and ginger sauce. Very reasonable and good

If you're ever in San Fran, you must dine in this restaurant. I happened to come across it as I was walking down on Chestnut street looking for a place to eat. I had no idea about this place but one thing I know now, is that I loved it. I recommend it. The place is really cool, the food is made out of all natural ingredients, the portions are bigger than what other restaurants served. The staffs are friendly and so are the owners. I had the Teriyaki tofu which was delish.

result.adr_address: 3345 Steiner St, San Francisco, CA 94123-2706, USA
result.formatted_address: 3345 Steiner St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Izzy's - San Francisco, CA

result.reviews.text: Never a bad meal, been eating here on a regular basis for the last 7 years. Love it, don't change!

My boyfriend took me for dinner. We ordered Maker's Manhattans. Our server suggested another kind and ensured us that we would enjoy them or he'd replace them. They were AWESOME (wish I could remember the name) I had  the lamb shank was deliciously tender and the creamed spinach, simply  amazing. The only drawback was we couldn't get a table to sit side by side since we were a party of two! Other than that, we will definitely return. I want two of those delicious Manhattans!!
They took all our special requests even though very busy! Service was great also. Food excellent both times!

We were visiting from Florida and were staying in the Marina district and wanted something different from the tourist attractions of fisherman's wharf.   Izzy's didn't disappoint.  My girlfriend had the drunken shrimp and I had the prime rib.   Bother were outstanding.   I would recommend the izzy's potatoes on the side.   A scalloped potatoes dish that was great.

Best meal ever. Best steak i ever had. The atmosphere is old san francisco. I can envision celebrities coming in with there pinup model girlfriends. The prime rib is amazing; juicy and seasoned well. The sides are equally well such as the potatoes and creamed spinach. Well worth the coin.

result.adr_address: 3348 Steiner St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 3348 Steiner St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Saiwalks, Vietnamese Street Food

result.reviews.text: I just love pho! and this place did it right. Staff was fast and friendly and the place has a nice ambiance and level of cleanliness. A good spot for a date night and awesome street food and pho.

Gluten free coconut crepe! So darn good!!!! Great place to go with your dog  and excellent customer service. Thank you Stephanie for always taking great care of us. This is my dogs favorite restaurant, she loves the servers here.
Not sure what the Street Food reference was, but this place is pretty good, relatively high-end Vietnamese. Don't forget the Mochi to end your meal :)
Great Pho!! Hormone free meat! One of the best pho's i have eaten.

Vietnamese catered to the masses...aka white people.

It was the saddest, most flavorless pho I've had in a while. Pretty disappointing considering it was $13 for a small bowl. I should have known better coming to eat pho at the Marina rather than at the Tenderloin, but the other half of the group was pretty content on coming here. The husband and I both got the beef pho and doused our bowls with siracha and oyster sauce to boost the flavor. The broth didn't even have the beefy, meaty flavor. Not to mention the bean sprout and herb plate they gave us was only enough for one. I must say though, the quality of the meat in the pho was pretty good. It's a shame there was no flavoring whatsoever. 

One weird thing was our table was next to a plug in that barked. Yes, you read that correctly... a wall plug in that projected dog barking noises every minute or so. When we asked the waitress if they could remove it since it was very loud and interrupting, she just said it was put there by the boss and she can't remove it. Then she just ran off, no apologies, explanations or attempt to remedy it. HUH?!  

Won't be back.

result.adr_address: 3352 Steiner St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 3352 Steiner St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: The Plant Cafe Organic

result.reviews.text: Delicious selection of afforable healthy eats at a good price. Very accommodating to special diets. This location has the most options with cocktails, brunch, etc. I have to take off an entire star because THERE IS NO BATHROOM. They will tell you that the common bathroom out on the pier is open but more 50% of the times I've been there it has been closed for cleaning and locked for HOURS.

Rude service, way over priced!!! I ordered yellow curry $12.50 with extra $5 shrimp to go, when I opened up my order, I was shocked to see all my food thrown in a oversized to-go box. The yellow curry lacked flavor, there was barely any rice/curry and it probably had about five baby shrimps inside.

$28.57 wasted

Huge decline in food and service. Huevos rancheros used to be a highlight, they now look like vomit and taste like mush. Apparently, no espresso nor fresh juice drinks on weekends. Most recently, they got my order wrong twice.

So not sure what the other reviewers experienced but I had the chicken tikka wrap and it was super tasty. A light spicy kick but not overwhelming and full of flavours. The sashimi is half off during happy hour and delicious.

Awesome sushi! Very fresh, very delicious. Two tips:
1) Get the Tuna Poke Tostadas! They're tuna avocado and mango on little round puffy chips and they are delish. Very unique. We order them every time.
2)  Try to make it for happy hour which is 5:30-7pm M-F. It's the same sashimi either way, but in those hours you'll get 20 pieces for $20 instead of $40.
The food is pretty good, but you come here for the atmosphere. We had an amazing server named Marley. She was attentive, kind, and funny. Our service was really excellent.

This place is so cute! They have an outside eating area and a Great menu of yummy burgers to choose from. The falafel is my favorite. My date was making fun of me for ordering it, but after he tried it he was singing its praises :)

Comforted to know the beef is sourced from Niman Ranch (grass fed, no GMO etc). Solid place for burgers, a bowl of chilli smothered with cheese, onion rings, milk shakes. Nice to be able to sit outside on a warm day.

Outstanding burgers but HORRID SERVICE. We sat for 12 minutes before a server came to the table, then another 10 before drinks came, and then 10 more before the food.  The fries were cold- though tasty despite that so would imagine they are delicious straight out of the kitchen.  The burgers were all amazing...but unless you have 30 to wait before you want to eat,  I would go elsewhere.

First day in San Francisco and we ended up tired and hungry after a long drive to this awesome place, which will be very hard to top this place. The hamburger was exquisite, customer service is over the top, and the place is very nice decorated. In addition, they have a closed patio with heaters when its cold.

result.adr_address: 2175 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.formatted_address: 2175 Chestnut St, San Francisco, CA 94123, USA
result.name: Delarosa

result.reviews.text:
I am absolutely a fan of authentic Italian food and I hope I can say with a little humility that I know good Italian food when I eat it. Delarosa is on point.

We didn't get too many entrees so I want to come back for more, but we decided to keep it simple - a classic margherita pizza with burrata and the pasta mezzemani.

We opted for spicy marinara in the pizza and it was the best decision we made. I was surprised by how spicy it was! My friend couldn't handle the heat but I thought it was just enough to not take away from the other flavors. It had a rich tomato flavor and the burrata was pleasurably creamy! The basil was unusually patted on after the pizza left the oven, but it was really nice because you got the full hit of that tomato basil combo.

The pasta mezzemani was new to me. Mezzemani looks like a slightly shorter rigatoni, and scamorza is a smoky mozzarella that paired really well with the baked eggplant! Definitely a winner.

We came in around 11pm (pleasantly surprised it was open late for such great food) and the ambience was very modern - music was bumpin (hip hop, r&b, pop, etc.) with all the people there, it was loud but still conversation friendly. We also got some interestingly flavored beers which were on tap.

Overall a solid 5 in my bookmarks, I would definitely recommend this to anyone who likes great Italian food

The place is  conveniently located in the heart of the city. Quite buzzing and always full of people. That's what baffles me. My experience would say otherwise. We went for a dinner on a busy evening. 

Ambiance: 
The place has a good ambiance. The seating is good and lighting could be better but not too bad. A little cramped, so you may be rubbing arms with someone or the other as you make your way in or out. 

Food: 
Being a vegetarian, I wouldn't give any comments on the non-veg part (that may be good). But as far as vegetarians go, you may not be missing something if you give this restaurant a skip as there are many far better places to have your meals in this lively city. We ordered Burrata Bruchetta as an appetizer, followed by Mezzemani pasta, a Margharita and a Spinach pizza. While burchettas were okay and pasta were good, pizzas were disappointing as they were quite greasy and very chewy for a thin crust. There is as much dough I can tolerate when I order a thin crust pizza. 

Service: 
Service was quite slow although the lady taking care of our group was well behaved. I would tend to attribute slow service to the rush hour but I am not sure if that's the case during non-rush hours as well or not. 

However, I shall give this restaurant a pass, given the quality of restaurants that are there in San Francisco.
great food. really impressed with the service and atmosphere. great for an after work dinner or drinks.

Good food, bad service. The cocktails and pizzas are good, however the service was extremely slow. Table seating is communal, which makes things get really noisy when it's crowded, and that combined with the music they blare overhead (why? when it's crowded it just adds to the noise while being indistinguishable from the overall roar of the crowd), you can't hear the person sitting across from you. 

Overall a fun place, but don't come during peak hours because they don't know how to handle it.
Good spot both food and drink wise. The burrata margarita pizza was awesome.

General:

Poppy seed.  Chive cream cheese.  Or smoked salmon cream cheese.  Tomato.  Sprouts.  Capers.  Now that's a Sunday breakfast.

.

result.reviews.text: Patio is unique and good. Food not so much. Hostess dismissive and distracted. Service was okay. For the price I'd expect much better. Mussels and clams way too small and overcooked! Perhaps frozen? Rice in the paella had been in a warmer much too long, was sticky and mushy. What I'd expect to find in a cafeteria. Would not return.

Food was delicious; we had the salmon to start, risotto, and chicken dishes for main, and gelato dessert. 3 courses for 30 dollars which was very reasonable considering the area. Will be back!
Can't believe the last time I was there was 5 years ago. This time the food is just as good as before. The famous potatoes wrapped cod was a bit over cooked but nonetheless the food is still great.

For this price range, the food was definitely above average, but not the best. That being said, the dishes did seem larger than the average SF size entree.

What was amazing was the service. Very attentive without managing to disturb our discussion.

Let me just put this out there: two things:
1. Isa has bomb ass bread
2. Isa hands down has consistently one of the best value DAT menus in SF

WOOT Clearly I'm a fan. I apparently went here when I was younger with family, but didn't remember. Isa has a cute dark cozy interior, and also a covered, awesome back patio area that doesn't get too chilly at night (BIG PLUS in the city). 

I've only been to Isa for DAT--the last two seasons--and they don't skimp on the menu: plentiful choices for all FOUR courses, unlike many restaurants that give you shabby little 2-3 courses for the same money. Scallops were huge and really nicely grilled--my cousin's fiancee enjoyed his duck--my main squeeze liked his fish. They grill really nicely at this place. I'd say the highlight was probably the apps--we shared mussels, tuna tartare, dungeness salad, and smoked salmon app (like bruschetta but with salmon...name is escaping me atm). The soup at the beginning was tasty too. Dessert was tasty too! Chose between creme brulee, grapefruit granita, and this almond italian dessert whose name is also escaping me @_@

Danger: The bread is good. It comes warm and the crust is delicious. Otherwise read as: BEWARE FOOD COMA because the bread just keeps coming and the water keeps pouring, and sooner than you or I know, you'll be full before the entrees even come. Learn from the mistakes of others. :)

result.reviews.text:
I think the best dish we had was the Uni Hotate. The delicate, sweet scallops paired pleasantly well with the richness of the uni. Not too much tamari was used so its saltiness was able to enhance the flavors without overwhelming the sweetness of the seafood.

The grilled items were generally decent also. The beef tongue was grilled on the rarer side and sliced really thinly. This made the texture less firm compared with other times I've had beef tongue, which I kind of liked. I also enjoyed the pork jowl. It was well seasoned and grilled nicely so that the fat inside rendered out as I bit into it. My friend didn't enjoy that some pieces were 90% fat, but I wasn't bothered by that. Just be wary if you're not a fan of fatty cuts. 

I have to add that I didn't find the tsukune to be very good. The meatballs were grilled well, but they were pretty bland. I'm guessing there's not much else that goes into the ground chicken when they make them. One thing I found particularly weird was having water chestnuts in the tsukune. I can see how their crunchiness can contrast with the soft ground chicken, but they didn't add anything in terms of flavor. 

The biggest disappointment had to be the ramen. We ordered the Miso Tonkotsu Ramen, and we had a hard time tasting either the miso or the creamy pork bone flavors in the broth. I noticed that there was a lot of cabbage in the ramen, which probably diluted the flavor of the broth. Compared with other ramen joints, this one unfortunately ranks pretty low. Especially for $12+, a ramen that's short on flavor is a huge blunder.
If you like the idea of "Japan" but you've never been to Japan this is the place for you. Interesting takes on certain dishes but overall disappointing
So good. It's not really a traditional Japanese restaurant, but their spin on things makes for some great food. Definitely recommend.
Especially love their uni risotto, black cod, and miso ramen!

We enjoyed our experience here. Luckily we had a few people so we were able to try a lot of food. Everything was really tasty but the ramen was definitely the star of the show for me. The chashu and egg were perfect!

I would give this place a No Star! I went quickly on my lunch and have been working in the area for over 2 years & have never been to this place. I walk in and the person there seemed to ignore that I was standing there and then someone finally walked out to take my order. I placed my order for a steak plate and an horchata (total $15.50) which was a bit overpriced but I decided that it must be really good. As I was waiting for my order I looked around their very small store and I noticed that nothing in there had a price. I decided to look at my receipt to see how much was each individual item I had just bought and realized I had just spent $152.50 (WHAT?!?!). As I walked to the counter the woman walked out and without me saying anything she quickly said (in Spanish) "I know". I was in awe hearing that she knew and did not say anything to me and waited to see if I was the one to bring it up!! She then said she would take care of it. She then asked me to swipe my card (Again) for which was for the actual $15.50 and said I would get a full refund for the $152.50She even let me know she was the owner and her name is Dilsia. I gave her the benefit of the doubt and waited 2 days and decided to call the Restaurant because there was no refund in my account but to my surprise the number that is on Google & Yelp are disconnected numbers and I had to call my bank and they said it showed that there had been no attempt for a refund from this place back to my account. I quickly requested a to make a claim and will have to have my bank deal with this situation. The steak plate was not that good, it was edible but not worth what they charge. I will not ever step foot in there again nor will anyone I know because I will make sure to tell my coworkers, friends, family, and our customers never to go in there. Don't come here they seem and from other reviews on her and on Yelp they are really shady when it comes to money!

result.reviews.text: This place has the best coffee!!! The food is high quality and a great price. I love the Mary's sandwich and the salad with house vinaigrette. Don't forget to take home some pastries and bread that was made that morning! Definitely going back.

As an Italian moved to US I struggled to find decent bread. These ladies here brought my taste back the Italian suburb bakery. The bread is simply amazing. You have choices! different kinds daily and I finally can eat a crunchy crust bread. Love you ladies!

I've tried the paninis, pizza, coffee, and pastries and, they are all excellent. The attention is great, as well. 
As for the baked items, they are always fresh and a good combination of crunch and soft dough. The filing for the paninis/sandwiches and savory pastries is very creative and generous. 
The make great espresso and cappuccinos. 
The pizza is phenomenal, the dough and the toppings are very tasty.

The sandwiches, ham and cheese pastries, and in-house pizzas are incredible. Everything is so fresh and made with a lot of care. Also prices are some of the best in the city. Happy to see solid, affordable cafes still.

I live above this place. I try to make coffee in my kitchen but it is never as good as the cold brew downstairs at Fox and Lion. I also work from my laptop in here sometimes. I have the chocolate croissants warmed up and they have the texture of a pillow in which an angel rests its head, and the chocolate tastes pretty good too.

Oh yeah, and they have $5 sandwiches for lunch that are pretty awesome.

result.reviews.text: Old Skool Cafe was a great experience! We had a party of 18 and were handled very well. Everyone's food was perfect and Tammy and Jeannie did an incredible job making sure we were all happy. We will definitely be making this a stop on our future NorCal visits!

Please go and don't be put off by the neighbourhood. We were so glad we went because food was excellent for SF pricing and the staff are incredible. They really are the show. Their stories and the entire cafe just goes to show how each of us is capable of achieving a better life with hard work, grit, some help and some love. Very family friendly.
The pulled pork over cornbread was delicious. But the calamari was out of this world. 5 stars!
Food is fantastic! It's a great support system for all of the young adults learning real life skills.

Yet another fan of the peanut butter stew-- incredible! Love the service, decor and overall vibe of this place. There's been live music every weekend evening I've gone, so make a reservation! This place gets busy!

result.adr_address: 748 Innes Ave, San Francisco, CA 94124, USA
result.formatted_address: 748 Innes Ave, San Francisco, CA 94124, USA
result.name: Archimedes Banya

result.reviews.text: I stumbled upon this gem while on vacation from Seattle. I was a little reluctant at first upon hearing it was clothing optional. To my delight,  the atmosphere is so friendly and relaxing. It's 100% judgment free. Before leaving I had gotten a message from Jel-Wu,  and it was hands down the best message I've ever had. The company should give this man a bonus, and clients should give him large scale tips. This place is amazing,   I left this fine establishment feeling the best I've felt in a long time.  I recommend this highly to anyone who had a sense of adventure, likes to try new things, and loves a day at the spa. Thank you SF for this experience!

I've been coming to the banya since it opened, and it used to be amazing - sadly, a change in management seems to have occurred, and it's really gone downhill. What was once a beautiful, well-kept space is now sloppily maintained and poorly managed. 

A few observations from my most recent visit - elements such as lounge chairs, towels, and other amenities have been downgraded. Small environmental comforts and details have been neglected, or eliminated entirely. Plush white leather loungers have been replaced by plastic lawn chairs, 
spa quality shampoos and soaps have been replaced by basics, and PH balanced, chilled drinking water has been swapped for plastic jugs of lukewarm tap water (despite signage advertising the use of Kangen machines). While they used to offer little niceties (such as lotion and cotton swabs) in the ladies room, on my last three visits, they didn't even bother to refill the toilet paper (even after I complained). 

The delicious, freshly prepared menu is a thing of the past. There is no longer a restaurant on site - it's been reduced to a snack bar with preprepared food, and barstaff which is uninterested in either serving patrons or keeping the place tidy (there were still 4th of July decorations strewn about, on the first day of September). There was even exposed wiring in the dining room (not reassuring, as it is rumored that faulty wiring caused an electrical fire a few years back). 

The clientele seems to have shifted from a demographic which was multi-gendered, friendly, and respectful (including a large presence of older Europeans) to one which is largely male, and tends towards Bro culture. Quite a few folks seemed to be there looking for a hook-up (and I was there on a weeknight). The new marketing may have something to do with it - laser-printed posters with photoshopped memes of bears in sunglasses now advertise what used to be a classy establishment.

The staff are unengaged, and seem to be more interested in socializing with each other than in supporting the experience of their clientele. On my last visit, three people sat behind the counter (making a patron wait while they debated which robes they liked better), while downstairs the housekeeping continued to pile up. One staff member ended their shift, joined patrons in the spa area, and then spent his time making aggressive, unwelcome comments towards attendees - to the point that several patrons (myself, included) left early. 

After several years of loyal patronage, I'm unlikely to recommend the banya to friends and family - and I'm seriously questioning whether or not I'll make another visit, myself. Disappointing, as this used to be a truly classy, one-of-a-kind place, which offered a lovely and relaxing experience.

This is by far the best bath house in San Francisco.  Very refreshing and soothing with great sauna, hot tub, and cold plunge.  Most customers are friendly and they visited at least twice.  Only downside is no hair dryer in the locker room.

This place is terrible. My Massuese Monique seemed to hate her job, and was not in the least bit intuitive or caring.

Thewater is so over chlorinated on the hot tub my eyes were stinging while sitting there (without getting my face wet). The place is full of loud, rawdy guys who are usually a bit drunk while naked. The clothing optional usually is fine in most places but it's clear there is no spa etiquette here.

Lastly, the perk of the place is the roof deck with a view if the bay and the city--too bad they let people smoke cigarettes up there! That totally ruined it for me. This is clearly not a detox expetience.

This was my first and last time. Oh and the front desk gals were uninterested in orienting a new client to the proper pick up locales for services so we were a few minutes late for our services.

In short, don't bother if you want to detox and relax.
Love to go here with my partner. I feel rejuvenated every time after I come here. The dry/humid steam rooms does wonders to the skin.

I ate at the food truck near AT&T Park. The hot link was cold. Asked for it to be heated up. It was returned cold again. They stated they didn't have a grill and the steamer was the best they could do. The temperature it was served that could not be considered healthy. I would not do again.
Five star ribs. Best corn bread and awesome tri tip. You can't miss this place. I can't wait to go back.

result.reviews.text: Nicely remodeled local Thai restaurant. Food is above average for type of fare and decent pricing although can take a while to arrive.
Something was wrong with this place. I ordered a beef dish to go and when I got home opened it. It smelled foul and tasted spoiled.

what a great hidden gem in the west portal area. it's on Claremont so slightly out of the way, but thank goodness for that because all the other restaurants are always jam packed. 

we ordered:
spring rolls (I recommend passing on these, nothing special)
jerky - amazing with a great sauce, most distinctive of the appetizers
calamari - very good also
chicken wings - had a sweeter sauce 
lettuce wrap - had a nice ginger flavor, light, not greasy

mains
panang curry - clean taste, good quality beef, large portions
Prince curry - has a nice kick with a unique flavor
pad Thai - fine noodles, light on the fish sauce which we prefer
duck volcano - mostly a veggie dish with some duck, so don't order if your expecting a duck dish 

service has been friendly and very attentive. highly recommend!
It was a very good restaurant, all waitresses and waiters were very nice and were all native to Thailand, extremely good food

My husband and I stopped there for a bite three weeks and we had a great experience! Service was outstanding, the broth for the appetizer clams was unbelievably flavorful, the pizza and its crust delicious with the organic Chianti they have as an option. The zabaglione for dessert was out of this world!
Too bad we live on the East coast!
Margherita Pizza and a glass of Pino Grigio made our early dinner memorable! Super friendly but not overwhelming service. A definite must stop-by!
Casual looking place with seemingly fancy food.  The bread is AMAZING.  Everything I've had here has been great.  Fast service as well.
Authentic Italian ambiance, spaghetti are with just the right amount of sauce.

Realistically, besides sushi, this is my absolute favorite restaurant. Absolutely amazing food, service and wine pairing. Food is to die for! Absolutely everything and anything you try is remarkable. There are many amazing restaurants in SF, this one is definitely top.

result.formatted_address: 820 Ulloa St, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Submarine Center

result.reviews.text: The sandwiches here are toasted just right. I have tried the hot pastrami, meatball, mixed Italian meat and tuna. I wasn't so crazy for the Italian sausage used in the Italian sandwich and the tuna is not the best I've had but the sandwiches are filling and decently good. Lines are usually not long but one time I went there during lunch and it was quite packed. I usually order ahead of time using Eat24 and they have always delivered on time. I just walk in, say my name and walk out with a sandwich. Worth a try if you're into sandwiches.
Not bad. Not the best hot-submarine sandwiches but not bad either. Great family spot, been going here for year!

The subs are amazing! The bread is toasted perfectly to have a crisp shell and yet the bread is airy and fluffy, toppings are fresh and well portioned. My girlfriend doesn't eat meat so I was worried her selection was limited but she loved it. Potato salad was awesome as well, good spices and better than my families for sure! 

I will definitely be back for more, had half at the shop and picnic'd the other half a sub, so satisfying. Also they are FAST, slingin' subs very well.
Just great subs and fast good service. I love this place!!

I was very surprised.  This turned out to be one of the best Hot Pastrami's I've ever had in my life, and dare I say the best in San Francisco... and I eat a lot of Pastrami Sandwiches, since it's my "go to" whenever I'm at any sub shop.   The service was crazy quick and professional!  I was actually in a bit of awe watching the guy make my sandwich! You seriously need to try this place!! You can thank me later. Best subs in SF, hands down!

result.adr_address: 1 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.formatted_address: 1 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Squat & Gobble

result.reviews.text:
Really solid food and quick service. Standard brunch  items on the menu - like sandwiches, eggs, and burgers - but also pad Thai and wok dishes. 

Their bloody Mary is of the standard lefty o'douls variety, with a bit of spice to it. Garnish is classic lemon and Olive, with a celery salt rim. A classic bloody.

I had the salmon scrambler and orange juice. The scrambler was just ordinary. I feel it would have been better if they would have put in some additional veggies or spices in it. The salmon would be better if it was cut up into smaller bits instead of stringy like fajita beef. They would get more props if you can order some food like hash browns as an extra. Overal, just ordinary.

Squat & Gobble used to be one of my favorite breakfast spots, but my last visit was really mediocre. It was my first time back since they remodeled, and I was excited about heading back to one of my faves. The service was fast and friendly as usual- hence the 3 stars, but the food was meh and I felt a little overpriced.

Here's what we ordered:

Eggs Benedict - super basic, nothing special. 

Mama Mia Savory Crepe (Mozzarella, Parmesan & Cottage Cheese, Onions, Mushrooms, Spinach, Eggplant & Tomatoes, Topped with Marinara Sauce) - I had immediate buyer's remorse when I ordered it, but thought it was actually not bad. The crepe tasted like a pizza, but the eggplant was a little undercooked. 

I'll probably be back since Squat & Gobble is in our hood, but probably only as a last option.

I've been to this Squat & Gobble location many times when I was living in SF and NEVER had any problems.  I'm guessing 4 years made a big difference.

I was visiting the city for a couple days and wanted to hit up my favorite spots.  Squat & Gobble managed to make it into the mix and I almost regret it.  We went there on a Sunday morning around 9am.  Parking was easy and free since it was Sunday.  My sister brought her dog (medium sized...no more than 35 lbs...VERY well behaved).  

Upon entering, we were greeted at the register.  We took about 5-7 minutes to decide what we wanted and made our way up to the register.  After ordering and paying, we were told that we were not allowed to sit inside unless the dog was a service dog.  I asked if we could sit at the table right next to the door in the corner and was quickly reminded that we needed to sit outside...well the problem with that was that it was drizzling.

I understand not allowing dogs, but in a very dog friendly city, I feel like there should be a sign on the door.  Or at the very least, we should have been informed BEFORE we ordered.  Unfortunately, that wasn't the end of the poor service.

After being seated, the busser brought out our water and utensils.  10-15 minutes later, our food came out.  The food was pretty good as it always was, but the service is dragging down this entire review.  Not to mention, it got cold very quickly since we were outside.  After our food was brought out to us, we didn't see them ever again.  Not once did they come to see how the food was, see if we needed water refills, condiments, or anything.  

It was a very disappointing visit to Squat and Gobble and I just cant see myself returning after what happened (or didnt happen).
Mediocre, service was slow, odd, pushy to get us to leave when it was slow

Our new favorite! Kid friendly with patient and attentive service. Pizzas are delicious but the corn meal crust one is a step above everyone else. Generally easy parking, and right next to the movie theater.

Good food, non-existent service. The worst was the waitress who spend the whole evening talking to nobody but her friends at one table. Saw one dude get up and pick up a box for himself because nobody would stop by.
Nice large place that's good for kids... but the pizza was fairly flavorless and average at best.
This is a great place to eat. The staff are really friendly and the food is amazing. I recommend the cornmeal crust pizza.

result.formatted_address: 840 Ulloa St, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA

result.reviews.text:
No frills but high quality steak and burger restaurant.

Modest small seating area.  Not good for large groups.
Delicious steaks, burgers, and fried foods in a casual neighborhood setting. Feels like  Cleveland. So unfussy. Love this place.
Decent steaks. Fast service. Could use a little renovating.
One of the best Hamburgers in the city, loaded with flavor. You're going to need extra napkins when you're done. Bison burgers are spot on as well.

The lighting is a bit bad I'm the back room, but if you sit in the front it's great! 

We had to ask to get the tables cleaned and looking around looks like most of them could have used it. 

The steaks were fantastic though, both of us ordered a filet mignon medium rare and it was cooked to perfection. The steak was flavorful and melted in the mouth.

Going to try the burgers next.

result.formatted_address: 9 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Vin Debut

result.reviews.text: One of the nicest wine bar in the area. I absolutely love the warm olives. I ordered the roasted Brussel Sprouts. It wasn't what-not roasted enough for my taste so I asked the Cheft to roast the sprouts for me. The Chef had a "can do" attitude and going the extra mile to roast my Brussel Sprouts more and loved it!  Th sprouts taste and the flavors combined, it's Devine. I like this place! Will be coming back!! Wine prices are reasonable. Love my wine, Textbook,Chardonnay from Napa really taste absolutely good! Thanks Margo for the recommendation!

Finding the Vin Debut wine shop has been delightful. After trying a new McLaren Vale Shiraz at a luncheon, I rushed home with a desire to order the wine for delivery to Tasmania. To my surprise I not only located the wine on your store, but it was well discounted, easy to order and marketed along with other interesting wines from the area. What a treat and thank you for your great service.

result.adr_address: 850 Ulloa St, San Francisco, CA 94127-1117, USA
result.formatted_address: 850 Ulloa St, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA

result.reviews.text: I really liked my pork burrito. It had shredded pork, rice, and black beans. The pork was seasoned well.  It was nice and hot inside which not many burritos are that I eat. It is one of the most tasty burritos I had. I'm definitely going back.

Not a fan of their carne asada so tried to sub it for chicken in their California burrito but was told they don't do that. Like really? I call bullshit cuz the cook just looked bitchy and over it. How you expect to bring in regulars if you can't compromise.

I stopped here for the second time today and am impressed. The ingredients are fresh, they're not stingy with the fillings and it tastes good. In fact, I'm eating a carnitas burrito now. 

The best thing I like is the customer service. Both times I stopped they thanked me for coming in. I've been disappointed with my old standby taquerias lately where I've been treated as a work product and got home with the wrong order. Try it, you'll like, They're right next to West Portal Muni station if you're traveling to or from.
Easy, quick take-out for burritos. Salsa is very fresh and tasty. Polite and good service.
Burritos are big and quick. Their steak is to die for, and they don't stiff you on meat like other burrito places sometimes do. Very nice employees too!

result.adr_address: 60 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.formatted_address: 60 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Bursa

result.reviews.text:
Had dinner here with a couple friends a few days ago, and I thought it was pretty good. We first shared the appetizer combo and pretty much everything was at least decent. The falafel was flavorful and crispy, but the inside wasn't as fluffy as Sunrise Deli's. One thing I enjoyed was the Baba Ghanouj with its roasted, almost smoky nuance. It paired really well with the freshly grilled flat bread (pita or lavash?). 

I had the Beyti as my entree, and it came arranged around a big square plate. I was not expecting it to be like that at all. Although I thought the lavash wrapping could've been toasted or grilled to make it crispier, the beef and lamb stuffing was well seasoned. I think there was parsley and other stuff that gave it a nice herby highlight. Good food and big portions - can't complain about that.

Bursa has excellent Turkish food. I particularly liked the hummus and pita bread. The pita was fresh and chewy and had grill marks. One of my friends got the beef stroganoff and it was really tasty. I don't normally like that sort of thing but Bursa made fabulous stroganoff.
Have been here several times due to west portal location. Most dishes were really good (chicken and shrimp).. beef kebab wasn't as great as other options and likely would not order upon return.
Huge portions and nice ambiance! Best Turkish food in SF. Baklava is great, ayran needs improvement.
The best food and service by far 👌🏽.......will definitely come back again.

result.adr_address: 50 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127-1304, USA
result.formatted_address: 50 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: El Toreador

result.reviews.text: Great place to bring anyone who would want to enjoy some of the best mexican food in town! Good for a family setting. I would reccomend anyone to eat here. Everything is delicious! The service is very nice!

This place has a cute décor, friendly staff, HUGE portions of food, and affordable prices – which is rare to find in the city. There’s usually a line up if you go around 8PM even in the weekdays; apparently it is a go-to place for a lot of locals in the neighborhood. First time we went there, we ordered 2 dinners for 3 people, and we had a good amount of leftovers! Their margaritas are pretty tasty, although you can’t find much tequila in them. Would definitely go back.

Delicious food! We ordered al pastor burrito, al pastor tacos, tortilla soup, and arrchera tacos. Gulped down everything. Only negative: found hair in my soup. They did replace it but the lady was not too nice about it.

Very different. Filled with tacky good looking stuff. One of a kind ambiance. Great service great food. 

You get salsa and chips as appetizers. Salsa is spicy but tastes amazing. I have been there almost 10 times and ordered almost everything. They all taste good.
Consistently good.   One of my go to spots.  Food here is more Tex Mex.  Very interesting & awesome décor.  Huge beer selection.

result.adr_address: 44 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.formatted_address: 44 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Quickly

result.reviews.text:
The rose milk tea is a bit too sweet but the boba itself is really good and so is the food! There are tons of options and the menu is lower down on the wall which is really great for visually impaired folks like myself.

 I used to live in the tenderloin walking distance from Japantown and I got kinda addicted to the takoyaki and bento box places there so it's nice to still be able to get my fix on that here in West Portal :) 

The location is great, the atmosphere is pleasant and the staff are nice.

I would definitely recommend the strawberry tea, the takoyaki and the waffle fries! The curry bento are also a great deal :)
They need help! Hire more staff..it took 30 minutes to get my drink.
Cleaner one of the quicklys

result.adr_address: 68 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.formatted_address: 68 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Calibur Inc

result.reviews.text: One of the best burgers out there at this price point! Perfectly cooked, juicy, fresh toppings, so impressive. And incredible customer service, the cook came out to say hello and offer me bacon because he had some on the grill, it was so personal and went above and beyond. They've nailed it!

Great burger and fries. The burger was juicy and flavorful. The fries were crispy on the outside and nice and soft on the inside. Definitely worth it. My only suggestion is for fountain drinks as an option instead of cans.
awesome burgers and an immaculate attention to detail down to their delicious calibur ketchup. not to mention the best hospitality and customer service i have ever experienced in sf.
Classic, retro burger joint. Nice service, great food. Recommend geting the burger "calibur style" and adding cheese to your fries for a bit extra.
Super solid burger. These guys source their meat from the best. You can get a great all-American burger/fries/shake experience here.

result.adr_address: 24 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.formatted_address: 24 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Fresca

result.reviews.text: Don't get me wrong this place would be 4 stars if I had gone with only my girlfriend.  Party of 5 went and shared 3 enteres, and 6 appetizers.  We finished with 4 desserts that were shared.  Our bill came out to be around 240 and I was not yet satisfied.  Although everything tasted good I wish the appetizers were a better value. 5 yuca fries for like 10 bucks.

As an aficionado of South American cuisine. Be it Brazilian, Bolivian or Argentinian, I have to say FRESCA is my favorite South american Peruvian neighborhood restaurant. I wish it was larger, the noise level is high and parking?.... Well good luck with that.... But if you manage to get in the food is definitely worth it, a little expensive, but enjoy the roasted Peruvian chicken o,  exquisite Anticuchos:  translation tender beef  bites, and my favorite Lomo Montado : Beef, rice, salad with a sunny side up egg on top. Get a nice Cusquenha beer and you are all set....

There are a lot of different factors that effect the overall score - it could be i ordered all the wrongs things. You don't order pizza, at a mexican restaurant right? I think this is what happened tonight, considering that people praise this place. I will give it the benefit of the doubt that i just ordered the wrong items. 

The restaurant is self is tiny but really nice and cozy like most places in west portal. The staff was fast, nice and attentive. No problem at all! 

So i ordered the civiché. The waitress suggest one for me and i ordered a side of plantain chips as well. Like some people who tasted the civiche they either thought it was too sour/limey or delicious. I love lime and acidic foods, but this one like drinking lime juice and fish. Love the seafood and the nice touch of spice, but way to much acid. Take that statement with a grain of salt or their civiche (bad pun). 

The plantain chips were inconsistent. Some were thin and crispy while the other half was thick and old. 

I normally get scared to try something else when i already had two strikes out and all the entrees were over $25. So i went on the safer side - steak salad. The salad was pretty normal stuff. i could make it at home - fajita style steak placed on a bed of greens with vinaigrette sauce. 

Overall i had an OK experience, nothing bad enough that i would scare people away from here, but i wouldn't mind coming back to try another thing on the menu.
One of my favorite places for brunch! Their ceviche sampler is delicious!
Food was great!!! Thank you

result.formatted_address: 118 W Portal Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127, USA
result.name: Rain Tree Cafe

result.reviews.text: Falafel wrap is delicious. Generous quantity. Slightly pricey but definitely worth because it's neat and clean. Nice service too.

Hi unfortunately I can't find a way to contact you privately so I have to post this on here. Yesterday I felt fine until I boarded my plane after eating here. I just had hummus and a beer and then for the rest of my 5 hour flight I was throwing up and running to the bathroom. I'm worried that maybe the vegetables or hummus or something will make people sick. So I just hope you as an establishment look into this. I apologize again for making a public statement, but there is no way to contact you privately.

There were exactly 9 seats available on tables and 0 on the bar, they told me they could not accommodate my one seat and two bags because they were busy even though there was absolutely no line. I could not sit at a table and have drinks.

As soon as my husband and I walked in we could tell that we were unwanted guests. The place smelled and the servers were unsanitary. After deciding to stay, we sat ourselves. The waitress came to our table and pretty much rushed us to put in an order. She wouldn't even allow me to finish my statements. To be honest, I don't think she wanted to serve us because after we ordered I seen her talking to another server (probably asking her to serve us instead). The restaurant was not busy. She had no other tables to serve! When the food came, the OTHER server bought us our meal. My husband order the cab cake dinner and I order a Reuben. His crab cakes were wet (uncooked) and had very little crab in them. My Rueben was soggy and the meat was very salty! The only thing about both our meals were the French fries. Since we were so hungry from touring the city, We ate our fries and then asked for the bill. The manager offered to comp the meal but we declined. He never apologized, not once. The only reason I gave this place one star is because there was no option to give no stars at all. Don't go here unless you just want a cocktail or a beer. Thu shouldn't be serving food. I'm not sure why people have been giving more than 1 star.
Slow service. $60 for 2 barely toasted English muffins and 3 drinks. Won't be back.

result.reviews.text: I had 1.5 hr to shop around in San Francisco Airport, my wife, friend and his wife, and myself decided to get something to eat at Tomokazu. The food was average ( "Mall Japanese Food" at best ). The staffs did not look too ( "Sincerely" ) nice. Hey, maybe it was because it was after 10 PM and they were tired? Anyway, the waitress / owner were looking at our table when we were leaving. While at our gate (500 ft away) waiting for our flight, I realized my wife left her UNOPENED coke bottle. My friend (extremely nice man) went to retrieved the bottle. You are right, he came back empty handed! They told him they had thrown the Coke away. Well, I don't believe in too many Conspiracy Theories, but I will go out on a JFK's Tombstone and say they resold the Coke. Do Not Eat Here!!!!!!!!! Look up Sam in New Orleans.
Friends had Sushi and i had Chicken Teriyaki, it was very good, especially for an Airport cafe. Also - the server was a cutie :)
The tempuras are all cold. This is the second worst Japanese restaurants except the one in NYC.
Love this place. Been going to their main location in Burlingame since I was a kid!

result.reviews.text: One of the best airport dining experiences of any airport. Great local cuisine without a big airport premium. I usually get chowder in a bread bowl, but I opted for the California veggie sandwich this time. Yum!

Food: 4
Decor: 3

Came here for lunch on my way to Miami.

1. Turkey Avocado artisan sandwich
~Pretty good, especially considering it's airport food. 

I'll definitely be dropping by here a lot in the future.
Great sourdough bread to purchase and used on sandwiches. My favorite is the turkey and havarti on sourdough roll. Fast service and to go service is available. Good cookies too.

When I can't make it down to the Fishermans Wharf, the next best location is right in SFO Terminal 3!  Nothing like a hot sandwich on fresh Boudin sourdough, after a Red-eye from Hawaii or Japan.  They even serve Peet's coffee.  So, Then you must grab some Haystack's to go,  to satisfy the sweet-tooth.

The counter staff was whispering half the time when she was taking our order, could barely hear her. It was end of the day, so I guess they are probably really worn down. 

Soup and bread tasted yummy, as expected of boudin bakery. Ordered two cookies to go which was good too. 

Plenty of seats at least during the time I was there.

expensive, burnt food with awkward service.
Why are they angry and ever respond me with good attitude ? I said thank you more than 5 times but never ever heard any answers. just ignored the existance of customers.
I will never forget this restaurant and will not visit here ever again. 
But why did I give tip? maybe to avoide argument with the guy. I regret that now.
Not bad for a quick bite before a flight. Decent, quick service and up market bar style food.
Had plenty of time to kill so wasn't worried about service time. Sandwich was just OK but prawn appetizer and butterscotch pudding dessert were crazy good.

A bright and inviting bar with a terminal corner spot that's ideal for people gate jumping. SFO gets their seafood delivered daily to their restaurants and this is the only place here that gets fresh oysters.

They are pricey at $18 for a half dozen. 5 of 6 shucked to perfection, meaty, briny, tons of lemon and some other dipping sauces that I chose not to use. Very good, best I've ever had in an airport. Expensive though. Crab Louie uses fresh crab, delicious. They could have crumbled the egg more and man those butter lettuce leaves were almost too big, a lot of cutting, but a true and proper crab Louie. I don't even know how much it cost but my bill was expensive at $60 for 2 beers, crab Louie and the oysters. The beers come quick and the bartender is ok, but the food is painfully slow. I waited 30 minutes for the oysters and another 10 for the salad. Service for the beers were only fast because the bar seating is close and small.

The menu seems small, but really isn't. If your only stopping off in SFO on a layover and can't get into the city for some of their finest this is your 2nd best bet and it's really not that bad. Vape friendly, but very out in the open. Bathroom right across the way. It seems like they have the bartender, a manager, and maybe 2 cooks so a pretty skeleton crew even when busy.

The popcorn shrimp come with a spicy cocktail sauce. They would be awesome without it but they are on another level with it. The service was quick and there is plenty room for seating especially considering this is in an airport.

result.reviews.text: Ridiculously surly staff that TRULY hate their jobs. Wow. Lots of yucking it up and curse words in spanish ( like I don't understand ) with each other but like zombies with customers. Was asked twice what kind of meat I wanted on my chicken burrito ! Just read the reviews about food poisoning and double charges and wishing myself luck. Its no wonder they don't have a website, but it is a wonder that they have a contract to sell in SFO. I ordered the carnitas burrito. I thought I knew what I was doing, I thought I could handle spice. I didn't think it would have any effect on the 3 hour lecture that I had to give the next morning. I was wrong on all counts. I think I ordered the spiciest beast I could possibly have ordered. I saw the burrito as a challenge, now I see it as a life lesson. There may have been some tears... result.reviews.text: Our dinner, on Sat. 13 August 2016, was  completely unsatisfactory.  As a San Francisco resident, and 3rd generation native, I have come to enjoy and appreciate the various cuisines that SF restaurants have to offer-several of them in The Presidio.  BUT, Arguello definitely does not come anywhere close to other great SF restaurants.  When we entered the restaurant, the woman at the desk, JANET by name, did not greet us.  When I approached her, she was unfriendly and unwelcoming. We got seated, and our server, CHRIS, by name, came to our table.  That was the LAST time we saw him. We ordered and waited an unusually long time for our meals to arrive. The food was unattractively served, lukewarm and tasteless.  The four of us had swiss chard and corn enchilada, whole shrimp and snapper. We had to ask for utensils and Chris never returned to see if we needed anything.  After our meal, we waited a very long time for someone to clear the dishes.  And, no one asked if we wanted coffee/tea, etc., so I had to ask another server to get Chris so we could order coffee.  We saw a lot of servers just standing around chatting and laughing with each other, but we couldn't get appropriate service from Chris. We wanted to leave, ASAP, but couldn't find Chris so we could get our bill.  Again, we had to ask another server to find Chris so we could pay the bill and leave.  Our reservation was at 7:15. and we didn't leave the restaurant until after 10:30.  Most of our time was spent sitting and waiting for service.  Needless to say, we won't be returning to Arguello.  There's too many other wonderful restaurants in the City that make you feel welcome and serve interesting and enjoyable food.
Small menu, tiny portion sizes and massive prices. Would not recommend.

Apart from being told "we're out of ___________" multiple times, we made our selection from the small menu that even the waiting staff has a hard time pronouncing. We asked one member what a word meant, they did not know what it was and never came back with the answer. The chips and salsa were pretty good. Extra of course. We get our meals and they were lackluster for the price. The ice cream sandwich dessert is brought with a knife, which is highly necessary to try and break the cookie. A steak knife or a machete would be a better tool to tackle that with. So, overall, the food didn't match the price, but, to be within a building stocked with military history...that part was pretty cool.
We had lunch here. Margaritas are amazing!! Food is fresh, service is fast. Very good.
A great place in the Presidio good tequila selection outdoor seating by a fire

result.reviews.text: It's ok if you are ok with the prices. The food is good, but the price point could leave you wondering if it was really "that" good. For tapas, I recommend going old school authentic to Alegrias on Lombard. It's not far away, the food and sangria are considerably better, and just a tad more reasonable in price.

Oh my gosh this place was absolute delight. I went here for a graduation dinner and let me just say everything was amazing. The bartender we got that evening was amazing, he was able to make me an non-alcoholic beverage even though we had to wait for our table at the bar because of a little mix up. But they redeemed themselves with their excellent service and wonderful employees! 

Now the food is something else I am still craving after going there 3 days ago! I dont remember the exact name and ingredients but the goat cheese and meatballs were heavenly appetizers and were portioned enough for you to be able to wait for your entree! I got the chicken and my aunt got the steak. We both loved it so much that I plan to take my friends and family whenever I get a chance to go down to SF again.

Atmosphere: the entire resturant felt homely and welcoming. The lights were not too bright and very luxurious.
Such amazing food but not the place to go if you're on a budget. I recommend sitting at the Chef's bar were you have a direct view to the prep and kitchen.

Excellent atmosphere, my love liked the Barcelona imported beer, the stake was on the dry side, but the presentation was very pretty. As for me, I love the rosemary bread, the patatas bravas & the albondigas. All three very tasty and the right size as to not overindulge; However, the cocktails... the grace kelly sandwich is super yums :)
