result.adr_address: 4318 California St, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA
result.formatted_address: 4318 California St, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA
result.name: Cafe Europa

result.reviews.text: European comfort food at its finest. This place can be overlooked because Inner Richmond is primarily known for Asian food. The owners are nice, the ambiance is cozy, and the food is great. I recommend the perogies, cream of mushroom soup, and the pork schnitzel. It's feels like I'm in Europe again. Will absolutely return.

I want to start by saying that I am Ukrainian and have tried many dishes at home and cook borsch a few times a week. Also, I have eaten schnitzel and bratwurst several times in Germany, so I have some experience with European food. I can say that the food itself is solid 3 stars. 5 stars for the the best European restaurant in town and very kind owner Alex. Average is 4. I hope this place will prosper and those who are looking for quality European/East European food will go to Cafe Europa and not to Red Tavern or Cinderella. 

Let's talk about food!

Borsch. I can agree with their claim that it is the best borsch in town, but I was not completely satisfied because traditional borsch always has pork or beef (for more flavorful bouillon) unless you request otherwise. I understand that there are many vegetarian folks out there, but then you have to cook two pots of borsch. I was willing to pay more for "complete set". Also, it is more on a sweet side, so I would suggest to experiment with recipe. As I said, my grandma cooked borsch, my mother cooked borsch and I cook borsch, so I know that it can be better :) But still... It's the best borsch in town

Cabbage rolls. Served with mashed potatoes and it is good sized entrée overall. Cabbage rolls are big and somewhat sour. Traditional recipe also includes rice in cabbage roll, so I would like to see it next time I come. Finally, I think that they are too big and it would be better to make 3 smaller rolls instead of two very big ones. Definitely, it is not major complain and better from what I got at Costco. 

Pierogi. I ordered pierogi with potatoes and beef and cab say that it is probably the best dish that I have tried for the night. It is very soft, tender, perfectly sized and served with sour cream.

Bratwurst. Might be the best appetizer for you if you ordered beer. It is is just very good appetizer to start your dinner. 

We also ordered salmon, schnitzel and lamb. Everyone was very happy. Lamb seemed to be very yummy. I would like to make a note about their bread. It is extremely good if not amazing and highly enjoyable with borsch. 

If you like beer, you won't be disappointed. They do not have exhaustive beer list, but I assure you that you can find something you like. 

Shout-out to the owner Alex, who knows some good jokes, make friends with clientele and provide small surprises during your visit! 

Bottom line. Some menu items can be better and there is always room for improvement, but it is the best European / Eastern European food spot in town, so you should check it out. Place itself is small and cozy with attentive service. I will be back and hope to see some changes.
Great Polish food made me feel missing home even more. If you like Polish food,  it's a mist go place.
Best Red Borscht ever. Staff is really friendly.  My new go to place when I get hungry for Borscht.
Friendly and attentive service, wonderful European fare, and a wonderful experience. The goulash was quite tasty.

result.name: Mandalay Restaurant

result.reviews.text: Mandalay noodles, tea leaf salad, and prawns were highlights. Friendly place. Cheerful décor. Satisfying, flavorful food.

Gave it a try. One time was all that was needed to realize my money could be spent elsewhere for both a more enjoyable experience, faster service, and generally better tasting food of this type. San Francisco has so many restaurants to choose from that I am sure that I will not miss anything by not venturing into this restaurant again.

Ps. The dishes treated of bleach/dishwasher soap.

Absolutely amazing. At first the color scheme and iridescent lighting may be off putting, but this place is a real hidden gem. Everything is extremely well flavored, and is a spot I go to almost every time I am in the SF area. (Get the Mandalay Special noodles).
I go here alot and the flavors are amazing and flavorful! I really recommend the mango chicken and balada.

Honestly, this place is amazing -- hands down. The times I've been here, their service has been consistent as well as the food.

I've tried their: Balada, Mango Chicken, Volcano Beef, Tea leaf salad Mandalay Noodles and Tapioca Coconut Drink. 

There is truly nothing like it in LA. Best of both worlds (Indian/Thai).

result.formatted_address: 4454 California St, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA

result.reviews.text: A really friendly cafe with deliciously gooey cookies! I had a great iced green tea, which was really refreshing and came in a huge glass. Newspapers and free wifi will keep you well entertained, plus people-watching the cheerful people who come in!

Although I can't tell you what to order here, I can tell you it's a fantastic place to meet and work on your laptop. Plenty of outlets to plug into and good WiFi. Quiet atmosphere,with just enough fresh air and commotion to keep you motivated. I ordered an americano and it was good, no complaints. I was there with a friend for a solid 5 hours working and enjoyed our time. Will definitely be returning.
Really popular in the neighborhood. Great fast service. Good coffee and food
Love this place! Used to be my oasis for getting worm done from a very busy roommate situation in the neighborhood
Love this cafe, try bulgogi sandwich and homemade cookie

result.adr_address: 195 5th Ave, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA
result.formatted_address: 195 5th Ave, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA
result.name: The Richfield

result.reviews.text: Small, intimate space. Great coffee! I probably come here more than my financial advisor recommends. Staff is wonderful!

I wanted to like this place, but something was just missing. 

Ordered:

Cold Brew - I must say I was pleasantly surprised when I saw the barista put in coffee ice cubes instead of the #basic water cubes im my cup prior to filling it with that black gold. I was excited to be given that extra ounce of caffiene without my cold brew being dilluted. It was only after a few sips I began to realize that the ice had given my coffee that freezer taste..that old ice taste. Ugh. I think they have a promising concept, but the execution of protecting the ice has to be worked out. 

Bacon & cheese muffin - It was ok. Wasn't given an option to heat it up, but maybe it would have tasted better then? It had a good amount of bacon bits, but didn't have much of a cheesy taste.

All in all it was ok. I wouldn't say there'd be anything to keep me going back.

A great addition to the Inner Richmond when they opened in the early fall last year. The beans are their very own Snowbird brand. The friendly team pulls excellent espressos and makes some fine specialty drinks (the Brevano is my favorite treat). The food menu, while short, is tasty without a miss in the bunch. They've done a nice job sprucing up this funny space, making it a real neighborhood gem.
Fantastic food dishes. Charming ambience.
Love this place.  It is small but great.  Chocolate chip cookies are my favorite.

result.adr_address: 563 Ruger St, San Francisco, CA 94129, USA
result.formatted_address: 563 Ruger St, San Francisco, CA 94129, USA
result.name: Presidio Social Club

result.reviews.text: Great drinks but the food is mediocre. We went for the weekly Barbecue on the patio. Had the ribs which were served with "BBQ sauce" which was catchup and vinegar. The smoked ribs were awesome but their sauce totally kill our meal.

Okay- brunch is a must here! 

We like to come here with our dogs after a good brisk walk in the morning.

Being that it's in SF they provide with blankets if you choose to eat outside. 

Their beignets and hot Mexican cocoa are to die for and their drinks are device and satisfying.

And the service is awesome as well, we've only been here a couple times but they somehow managed to make you feel like a regular.

The beignets were great. Chef apparently ferments brioche giving them a nice flavour. Unfortunately the milk chocolate sauce wasn't rich enough to my taste but who cares when the beignets didn't even need it. 

Fries were perfect the way I like them:  thin and crispy.

We must have caught the kitchen on an off night. It happens.   
If I were to grade our meal I'd give it a C-.  Overall, the food lacked finesse. In addition, Presidio Social Club might want to bring its A game now that  2 Traci Des Jardins restaurants are right down the street from them. 

I've tried almost all of the desserts at PSC and for the most part I've been underwhelmed.  I can forgive the first or even main courses being somewhat disappointing, but dessert? Never.  I used to be a professional pastry chef  and I'd gladly wager a $100 that I could do  better job at re-inventing  what's on their dessert menu. I hereby throw down the gauntlet PSC.  Seriously, I could, without a doubt, prepare better versions of all of your desserts.
This love is great! Free parking, killer food and great fun atmosphere. Can't wait to make it back to this spot

result.reviews.text: The staff is friendly and service is quick. However, the dragon rolls and bamboo rolls were not that good. Also, this place is shown on the map as an average-priced restaurant. The restaurant setting and the food are average. But the price turns out almost the same  as if you go to a high end sushi bar.

Seems sweet (servers). Clean bathroom. Table looks dirty. As i sit back against chair and lean forward my shirt sticks.
Prices seem reasonable. Easy to read menu. Lots of choices.
Delicious green tea, nice cup.
Delicious tempura. Even the carrot, eggplant, everything tasted excellent.
Delicious soba noodles and broth.
Conclusion: they deserve better tables andr chairs.
Rest of decor nice: clean, small, peaceful.

2nd visit on a Friday night... Hopping busy but servers very attentive, efficient, personable.
Fast service.
Delicious.
Affordable prices.
Tip for parking: northbound 6th ave facing Cornwall: bus stop is open for parking after 8 pm!!!

Con: just tried Calif roll...too wet, tasteless. Picked ginger bad flavor (usually I love pickled ginger, but not theirs)

It feels a bit pricy, but it's definitely worth it.
Tanin Udon soup was flavorful and sushi were just great.
Friendly, simply wonderful authentic fresh sushi.
If you go there, only try sushis and shots. Those are the best.

result.reviews.text: Awesome gastro pub in the presidio. Insane beer selection and an extensive sour selection. Go for brunch and you'll be happy.

Five of us ordered nearly everything on the menu (ha! Perhaps a bit exaggerated) Each and every dish was absolutely deeeeelish! Creative yet not over the top in richness or heaviness , but thoughtfully  and creatively  presented. Must return again and again

They're situated right on the park and have a great outdoor space complete with space heaters and a high-walled glass fence to keep you protected from the elements. Our service wasn't particularly great, but the food was. We went for brunch and loved the potato pancake appetizer.

Probably a 3.5. The outdoor space is really great, awesome stop on a weekend afternoon. Indoor gives you an entirely different vibe and I probably wouldn't suggest going there to eat inside. Great beer selection, and food is pretty good, though clearly overpriced.
Good beer selection, had some hard-to-find offerings during a tap takeover. Decent burger, but expensive for what it was. Presidio is too far out for me, though.

result.adr_address: 3640 Sacramento St, San Francisco, CA 94118-1710, USA
result.formatted_address: 3640 Sacramento St, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA
result.name: Spruce

result.reviews.text: Excellent service! Wonderful wine selections! Very tasty dishes... 😋

The food and cocktails were both excellent here, although it is not a cheap meal by any means. Came here to splurge (had received a gift card here) and still ended up spending more than the gift card limit =\.

We sat at the room in the back, where there were three other couples (five tables in all). It was quiet, but the server was very attentive.

Food:
- Complimentary bread: Comes with butter and honey butter. 
- White Corn Soup: I love corn creamy soup. This tasted like what I expected, but there were some crunchy (grain?) bits in one region of the soup that were surprisingly good.
- Goat Cheese and Lettuce: Good, but it tasted like a standard salad. The goat cheese tasted very nice, but I say that about every goat cheese I've ever tried.
- Duck: Really tender and tasted a bit like steak (according to my boyfriend). We got melted foie gras on it.
- Bavare Steak: I had anticipated more like a large rib-eye steak (not familiar with Bavare), but it came out with 5 chunks and a more modest portion. That being said, I was completely stuffed after the meal and the meat was very juicy.
- Beignets: So good. Soft and light!

Cocktails:
- Eastern (?) - their version of the cucumber gimlet, except with mint. Loved it
- Caipirinha - I don't think it's on the menu, but their bar makes anything you want.
- Old fashioned: Relatively delicious, but not a "traditional" old fashioned. It had more soda in it
I began forgetting the next round of cocktails... but I vaguely recall them being very good as well.
Delicious lunch menu with prix fixe

Sat at the bar. Loved the Cesar salad. Typically not a fan but friend recommended it. Spaghetti was rich and creamy with a nice goat cheese, great to fare la scarpetta. Wish the bread would have been warm. Duck is nice. Beniets were amazing if not a bit much sugar on top. I expected 3 or 4, came with 8. Excellent service.
"Friendly knowledgable staff, hip ambiance.

result.formatted_address: 60 Clipper Cove Way, San Francisco, CA 94130, USA
result.name: Treasure Island Bar & Grill

result.reviews.text: The place looks a little old but once you are inside it looks good ! Excellent views of San Francisco and Oakland ! Food was good and well served ! Place is pretty decent ! 3 stars because of a stupid joke( Spanish-accent ) moking me perhaps becuase I am hispanic , that the waitress -bartender made while placing two tacos plate on table ! Not cool and totally uncalled for !

I discovered this place almost by mistake, going to Treasure Island Flea market on the wrong day. I am happy I did that mistake, since I this place became one my favorite places to go, specially when someone is visiting. It has very great views of the city. The food is good (I tried fish tacos and shrimp tacos and loved them) but also the cocktails are delicious. Try any of the different versions of Margaritas while enjoying the sunset over San Francisco.

Outstanding veggie quesadilla. And chargepoint electric vehicle stations right in front, so I can charge my electric vehicle as I eat. Two kinds of draft beer and $5 house wines too. Great views, but dirty windows, could be a little better maintained.

The bartender ignored me and my family until the waitress made her wait on us. She talked with the locals and had me stand at the end of the counter. She d8d not know how to make my drink. She was really rude until I tipped her well. 
The restaurant is very clean. It has board games and great view of Alcatraz, Bay Bridge and Golden Gate Bridge. Great outdoor seating with beautiful table decorations. Seashells everywhere. 
Very unfriendly staff (except waitress from Hawaii;however, the food was great! Had the best wings and fish tacos. Wish we wouldn't have eaten or stopped there because....

Treasure Island is a Superfund Site...a hazardous waste site. This one is radioactive waste.  It was totally abandoned and neglected closed Naval Base. The Navy contaminated this site and is being forced to remediate.  The area is to be a 5Billion Environmentally self contained real estate development. It will get back to safe levels...but, the people who lived there are dying from cancer and being forced from their homes. 

This type hazard will effect their DNA. 

There was no signs or any disclosure about this information.

I come here all the time. The regular staff are great, the food is fresh and made to order. You can eat inside and watch which over game is on or sit outside in their enclosed dinning space that has fun views of the SF's skyline, Clipper Cove Marina, and the Bay bridge/Yerba Buena island. Always a good place for well sized portions and good value.

result.formatted_address: Pier 5, The Embarcadero, San Francisco, CA 94111, USA
result.name: Coqueta

result.reviews.text:
I took my mom here for a fancy birthday lunch and they burnt our paella. When I complained that it was burnt on the bottom, they told me "that's the way paella is made". Umm, no. I'm Spanish. I've eaten paella in Spain. It never comes burnt like that. The rice on the bottom was literally black and inedible. What bothered me the most was how they told me I'm wrong. Who does that? 
They gave us a complementary cheesecake dessert which was honestly absolutely delicious. It's cheesecake made from manchego cheese. Wow. Very good. Will not be coming back though. I dropped 100$ on lunch because I wanted to treat my mom and I was served burnt rice.

This is the 5th times or more in the past 3 years. 

Make reservations. Walk in is hardly likely a good choice.

Food: I think i have tried almost 80% of the menu but still haven't get a chance to try the $80 steak, which requires a large party. Everything on the menu is worth to try out.

Drinks: Their cocktail is so pretty that your ladies will love it.

Mediocre. On the good side: Very beautiful surroundings in the restaurant and well portioned tapas. On the bad side: very noisy and the tables are very close, making it difficult to have privacy. So I would not recommend the place, if you go for a romantic dinner. Moreover, there are only two restrooms for over 100 guests, which means that you have to wait in line. Some of the tapas dishes I do not consider as a real dish. An example is the dish with a small green peppers. One can get the impression that the dishes do not quite fit together. Therefore, I recommend the restaurant that they have a prepared menu, which they can present to the customer.

I've been here twice and it is becoming a one of my favorites! The atmosphere is lovely and the food is delish! The staff is amazing, shout out to Chef, Ryan Patrick, Alex and Ericka!!  They are attentive and really work to know what you would like! Wait!! Did I mention the cocktails? They are beautiful and tasty. If you are looking for a great place to visit with friends or a delicious spot with your person... This is the place! 😄

Coqueta by Chef Michael Chiarello	(means “Flirt” or “Infatuation”  in Spanish) 

The beautiful Embarcardero location with its “Spanish Flair,” a view of the water, the small plates, the gracious staff and the incredible wine list is a must.  Inside, the soaring rustic space is very chic with reclaimed wood, oak table tops, and branded hides on the floors. 

The minute we stepped into the beautifully glass-enclosed entry, we were greeted by Ericka with her very warm and welcoming smile.
Marc Peyer, the Assistant General Manager, was very gracious and helped us maneuver through the tapas menu with his favorite recommendations as well as wine pairings.  
Marc understood our wine preferences and was spot on with his recommendations.
Our waitress, Darnelle, was very efficient, informative and a pleasure to spend the evening with.   A great staff and most enjoyable evening!

Our favorites included:
     Pulpo a la Parilla wood grilled mediterranean octopus,		
     freshly dug fingerling potato, pimentón olive oil $14

     Pintxos Bite-size Skewers (offered tableside) $2.50

     Salmón Ahumado Smoked salmon, queso fresco and 
     truffle honey $8

     Paella, The classic, made with bomba rice, jamón
     serrano-shellfish broth, Gulf shrimp, clams, chorizo with 
     Thumbelina carrots, pickled garlic scapes and lemon alioli,	
     $45 serves 2-3

     Pulpo a la Parilla wood grilled mediterranean octopus,
     freshly dug fingerling potato, pimentón olive oil $14

     “Gaucho” Bistec wood grilled bone-in 32oz natural beef
     ribeye with aromatic Moorish pepper   
     Serves 2-4 $84

      The shrimp and razor clam paella was the best I have 
      had.  Allow approximately 45 minutes for preparation.

       The rice was properly cooked to al dente and the large 
       shrimp and razor clams were in abundance.

        The bone in rib-eye was perfectly carved and just the right
        temperature of rare.  

        The Manchego Cheesecake bites were the perfect sweet-
        salty desert.

         The attention to detail on presentation throughout the meal 
         was a visceral journey.

result.name: Hard Water

result.reviews.text: Great bourbon and American whisky selection. The place was packed with costumed Halloween partiers when we were there, so service was pretty slow, but I'm guessing that's not normal. Very convenient location - halfway between the Ferry Building and the Exploratorium. The Brussel sprouts were very crispy and flavorful. One gotcha: unless otherwise specified, whisky prices are per ounce, but the standard pour is two ounces.
The food is okay. They need to dial the spirit list back down to reality. Not sure who is paying out the nose for those whiskeys, but it's very off-putting.

Good was fine and whisky collection good, but service was genuinely awful. We say at the bar and had to ask to order food, ask for drinks, stack our plates up to be cleared, etc. One of the barmen just wanted nothing to do with us, and the other was spending more time saying how stressed he was and complaining about his waiting team than helping anyone... Really poor experience.

A local friend mentioned that since I like Whiskey I should check this place out. I cannot believe how great an idea that was. I feel like flying back in to SF just to have an evening here with some lovely bourbons.
Nice selection of cocktails, great bourbon, love their bar snacks..got to try their pork crackling..so good.
